WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.952 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.952 --> 00:00:03.904 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.904 --> 00:00:05.368 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.368 --> 00:00:11.540 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:13.640 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: OK,
so let's continue

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:16.340 align:middle line:84%
discussing the proof of
Bourgain's projection theorem

00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:18.410 align:middle line:84%
and how it's similar
and different

00:00:18.410 --> 00:00:22.340 align:middle line:84%
from the corresponding statement
in the finite field setting.

00:00:22.340 --> 00:00:24.440 align:middle line:84%
So just as a quick
review because we

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:27.680 align:middle line:84%
are going to keep
working with this concept

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:41.000 align:middle line:84%
a delta, S, C, d set is
a subset of, let's say,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.480 align:middle line:84%
the unit ball or
maybe the unit cube.

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:46.530 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't really matter.

00:00:46.530 --> 00:00:49.400 align:middle line:84%
So it has to live in some
bounded region of space,

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:57.920 align:middle line:84%
such that, if we
intersect X with the ball

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:00.090 align:middle line:84%
and look at the
delta-covering number,

00:01:00.090 --> 00:01:03.080 align:middle line:84%
this is controlled
by, well, first

00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:05.209 align:middle line:84%
of all, this
tolerance constant C,

00:01:05.209 --> 00:01:10.910 align:middle line:84%
then the radius of the
ball to the power S,

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:17.670 align:middle line:84%
and then the size of all of X.
So it is a spacing condition,

00:01:17.670 --> 00:01:22.040 align:middle line:84%
and although this is not
part of the definition,

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:25.100 align:middle line:84%
it is convenient to
imagine that the size of X

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:28.140 align:middle line:84%
is maybe delta to the minus S,
although it doesn't have to be.

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:31.220 align:middle line:84%
But it is in the setting of
Bourgain's projection theorem,

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:33.980 align:middle line:90%
as I stated it.

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:36.800 align:middle line:84%
And speaking of Bourgain's
projection theorem

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:40.093 align:middle line:84%
as I stated it, let
me state the version--

00:01:40.093 --> 00:01:41.510 align:middle line:84%
well, not the
version, it's really

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:43.920 align:middle line:84%
exactly the same theorem
I stated last time,

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:45.740 align:middle line:90%
but using this language.

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:49.890 align:middle line:84%
So Bourgain's projection
theorem, again,

00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:52.160 align:middle line:84%
so it's really exactly
the same statement,

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:56.800 align:middle line:84%
just using this
language and rescaling--

00:01:56.800 --> 00:02:04.120 align:middle line:84%
suppose that X is in the unit
ball of R2 and is a delta--

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:05.920 align:middle line:90%
oh, sorry, quantifiers.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:14.960 align:middle line:84%
So given t between 0 and
2, S strictly positive,

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:20.650 align:middle line:84%
at most, 1, there exist
two parameters, epsilon

00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:24.400 align:middle line:84%
and eta positive,
depending on t and S,

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:26.710 align:middle line:90%
so that the following happens.

00:02:26.710 --> 00:02:36.460 align:middle line:84%
If X is a delta t delta
to the minus eta set in R2

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:47.710 align:middle line:84%
with size delta to the minus t,
and D the set of directions--

00:02:47.710 --> 00:02:48.876 align:middle line:90%
let's say in 0, 1--

00:02:48.876 --> 00:02:51.580 align:middle line:90%


00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:59.680 align:middle line:84%
is a delta S, delta
to the minus eta set,

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:07.870 align:middle line:84%
then there exists a direction in
our set of directions such that,

00:03:07.870 --> 00:03:14.710 align:middle line:84%
if you look at the minimum
over all subsets of X,

00:03:14.710 --> 00:03:19.480 align:middle line:84%
which are dense in the sense
that the delta-covering number

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:24.850 align:middle line:84%
is at least delta to the eta,
this tolerance parameter times

00:03:24.850 --> 00:03:32.090 align:middle line:84%
the delta-covering number of X,
and we project the subset, then,

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:34.520 align:middle line:84%
no matter how I
choose the subset,

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:38.690 align:middle line:84%
we get a gain over the, between
quotes, "trivial bound,"

00:03:38.690 --> 00:03:40.550 align:middle line:84%
which is less trivial
in this setting.

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:44.140 align:middle line:84%
But nevertheless, this is
at least delta to the minus

00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:46.660 align:middle line:90%
t over 2 minus epsilon.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:48.920 align:middle line:90%
So epsilon is how much we gain.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:52.010 align:middle line:84%
And delta 2 to the minus
eta is our tolerance.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:55.745 align:middle line:90%


00:03:55.745 --> 00:03:57.620 align:middle line:84%
This is really the same
theorem as last time.

00:03:57.620 --> 00:04:00.370 align:middle line:84%
Last time, X was in
the ball of radius R,

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:02.180 align:middle line:90%
and it was a unit of unit balls.

00:04:02.180 --> 00:04:05.140 align:middle line:84%
But we just scaled it down
by a scale of 1 over R.

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:08.410 align:middle line:84%
And by the equivalences
for measuring

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:10.820 align:middle line:84%
the delta-covering number
that I mentioned last time,

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:12.590 align:middle line:84%
this is really the
same statement.

00:04:12.590 --> 00:04:23.240 align:middle line:90%


00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:25.370 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we saw that
the following is true,

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:27.405 align:middle line:84%
even though we didn't
actually prove all of it.

00:04:27.405 --> 00:04:31.012 align:middle line:90%


00:04:31.012 --> 00:04:32.470 align:middle line:84%
Last time, we saw
that there exists

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:39.280 align:middle line:84%
a polynomial, which is just
X1, X2, X3 minus X4, X5, X6.

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:40.660 align:middle line:90%
That works.

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:43.660 align:middle line:84%
So it exists a
polynomial such that,

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:52.620 align:middle line:90%
for every S between 0 and 1 on--

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:54.670 align:middle line:84%
OK, I didn't say it
this way last time,

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:57.690 align:middle line:84%
but maybe let's introduce
also the two parameters here.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:04:59.680 align:middle line:84%
Last time, I stated
with just one parameter.

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:01.860 align:middle line:84%
Of course, you can just
take epsilon and eta

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:03.940 align:middle line:84%
to be the same by
taking the minimum.

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:07.620 align:middle line:84%
So the whole statement, if
you replace epsilon and/or eta

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:09.875 align:middle line:84%
by a smaller number,
is still true.

00:05:09.875 --> 00:05:11.250 align:middle line:84%
So we could just
take the minimum

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:12.700 align:middle line:90%
and have just one parameter.

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:15.180 align:middle line:84%
But I sort of want to
distinguish them because they

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.145 align:middle line:90%
play different roles.

00:05:17.145 --> 00:05:19.410 align:middle line:84%
So there exists
epsilon and eta such

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:31.340 align:middle line:84%
that if A is a delta S
delta to the minus eta set,

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:35.040 align:middle line:90%
it may be contained in 0, 1.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:39.090 align:middle line:84%
And maybe let's assume
also that the size of A

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:43.230 align:middle line:84%
is delta to the minus
S. Then the size

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:45.556 align:middle line:84%
grows by applying
this polynomial.

00:05:45.556 --> 00:05:52.610 align:middle line:90%


00:05:52.610 --> 00:05:55.990 align:middle line:84%
And we discussed that this
is not enough to iterate,

00:05:55.990 --> 00:05:58.500 align:middle line:84%
because in order to iterate,
we need to know that Q of A set

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:00.310 align:middle line:84%
also satisfies
these assumptions.

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:01.930 align:middle line:90%
And this is not clear at all.

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:03.720 align:middle line:90%
And in fact, it's not true.

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:05.453 align:middle line:90%
So we need to improve.

00:06:05.453 --> 00:06:13.020 align:middle line:90%


00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:21.090 align:middle line:84%
To Q of A contains A
delta S plus epsilon delta

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:25.200 align:middle line:90%
to the minus eta set.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.560 align:middle line:84%
If we knew this, then we could
iterate and keep growing,

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:31.320 align:middle line:90%
so keep adding epsilon.

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:33.550 align:middle line:84%
And because epsilon
is continuous in S,

00:06:33.550 --> 00:06:38.460 align:middle line:84%
we can get as close to delta
to the minus 1 as we want.

00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:40.990 align:middle line:84%
So today, we will
discuss how to do this.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:42.420 align:middle line:84%
So let me say that
it's not going

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:44.110 align:middle line:90%
to be the same epsilon and eta.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:46.110 align:middle line:90%
So they're going to--

00:06:46.110 --> 00:06:52.040 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they will become
much smaller, but same order

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:52.830 align:middle line:90%
of quantifiers.

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:54.470 align:middle line:90%
So there exists S--

00:06:54.470 --> 00:06:58.250 align:middle line:84%
sorry, for every S, there
will exist eta and epsilon

00:06:58.250 --> 00:07:01.260 align:middle line:90%
so that this is true.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:03.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is what we
are going to mostly

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.440 align:middle line:84%
discuss today and, hopefully,
then go briefly over how

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:08.760 align:middle line:90%
to finish the proof.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:11.870 align:middle line:84%
But I will say, this is the
main difference with respect

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:14.750 align:middle line:84%
to the finite field
setting, where we don't have

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:17.100 align:middle line:90%
to worry about any of these.

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:19.280 align:middle line:84%
So before coming back to
this, we'll take a detour,

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:22.080 align:middle line:90%
and then we'll come back.

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:28.520 align:middle line:84%
So let me state a lemma with
some basic properties of delta

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:30.740 align:middle line:90%
S, C sets.

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:39.606 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that X is a delta
S, C set in any dimension.

00:07:39.606 --> 00:07:44.840 align:middle line:90%


00:07:44.840 --> 00:07:47.960 align:middle line:84%
Then we make the following
two fairly easy but important

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:48.940 align:middle line:90%
observations.

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:50.690 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I should have
done this last time

00:07:50.690 --> 00:07:54.290 align:middle line:84%
to get some intuition about
what this concept does.

00:07:54.290 --> 00:07:58.710 align:middle line:84%
First of all, X is
large at all scales.

00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:02.840 align:middle line:84%
So the rho-covering number of
X is at least C to the minus 1

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:07.810 align:middle line:84%
rho to the minus S for every
rho between delta and one.

00:08:07.810 --> 00:08:11.000 align:middle line:90%


00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.430 align:middle line:84%
I mentioned in passing
last time that this is true

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:14.790 align:middle line:90%
for rho equals delta.

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:19.190 align:middle line:84%
But in fact, it's
true for every rho.

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:22.860 align:middle line:84%
And two, this concept is robust
under passing to subsets.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:27.980 align:middle line:84%
So if X or maybe
Y is a subset of X

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:31.460 align:middle line:84%
and the delta-covering
number is,

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:37.100 align:middle line:84%
let's say, 1 over K times the
delta covering number of X,

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:43.809 align:middle line:84%
then Y is a delta
S C times K set.

00:08:43.809 --> 00:08:46.490 align:middle line:90%


00:08:46.490 --> 00:08:51.440 align:middle line:84%
So the constant C gets
worse by the parameter

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.020 align:middle line:84%
measuring how dense
Y is in X, always

00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:55.390 align:middle line:90%
using delta-covering numbers.

00:08:55.390 --> 00:09:05.765 align:middle line:90%


00:09:05.765 --> 00:09:08.460 align:middle line:84%
So the proof of this
is fairly simple.

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:09.360 align:middle line:90%
So let's do it.

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:10.770 align:middle line:90%
We have to prove something.

00:09:10.770 --> 00:09:13.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, we need to show that
the rho-covering number is

00:09:13.430 --> 00:09:13.980 align:middle line:90%
something.

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:15.440 align:middle line:84%
So the definition of
the rho-covering number

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:18.210 align:middle line:84%
is the smallest number of rho
balls needed to cover the set.

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:22.370 align:middle line:84%
So let's cover the
set by rho balls.

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:24.300 align:middle line:84%
And let's see how
many balls we need.

00:09:24.300 --> 00:09:26.245 align:middle line:84%
So let's say we
cover the set by.

00:09:26.245 --> 00:09:29.390 align:middle line:90%


00:09:29.390 --> 00:09:32.570 align:middle line:90%
M balls of radius rho.

00:09:32.570 --> 00:09:36.110 align:middle line:84%
Well, then the
delta-covering number of A--

00:09:36.110 --> 00:09:38.480 align:middle line:84%
so the delta-covering
number is subadditive,

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:41.810 align:middle line:84%
something which will
come up repeatedly today.

00:09:41.810 --> 00:09:44.720 align:middle line:84%
And this is just because
if we have a delta cover--

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:46.850 align:middle line:84%
sorry, a rho cover--
sorry, a delta cover.

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:48.770 align:middle line:84%
We are covering by
[INAUDIBLE] delta now.

00:09:48.770 --> 00:09:51.410 align:middle line:84%
If you have a delta
cover of each of these,

00:09:51.410 --> 00:09:54.730 align:middle line:84%
we can put them together, and
we get a delta cover of this.

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:56.620 align:middle line:84%
So for this reason, the
delta-covering number

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:58.640 align:middle line:90%
is subadditive.

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:00.430 align:middle line:84%
So the delta-covering
number of A

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:04.390 align:middle line:84%
is at most the sum
of the delta covering

00:10:04.390 --> 00:10:06.915 align:middle line:84%
numbers of A intersected
with these balls.

00:10:06.915 --> 00:10:12.130 align:middle line:90%


00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:14.270 align:middle line:84%
But by definition of
delta-covering set,

00:10:14.270 --> 00:10:20.710 align:middle line:84%
each of these is at most
C rho to the S times

00:10:20.710 --> 00:10:26.230 align:middle line:84%
the delta-covering number of A.
So we have a uniform upper bound

00:10:26.230 --> 00:10:27.730 align:middle line:90%
that only depends on rho.

00:10:27.730 --> 00:10:29.120 align:middle line:90%
So the center doesn't matter.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:36.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is just the definition
of A being a delta S, C set.

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:42.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is at most M C rho to
the S delta-covering number

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:44.980 align:middle line:84%
of A. So we see that
we can cancel out

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:47.790 align:middle line:84%
the delta-covering number of
A, and we get the claim one.

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:50.380 align:middle line:90%


00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:54.820 align:middle line:84%
So we get that M is at least
what is on the right-hand side

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:55.760 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:10:55.760 --> 00:10:58.010 align:middle line:84%
But the smallest possible
M is, by definition,

00:10:58.010 --> 00:10:59.010 align:middle line:90%
the rho-covering number.

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:08.855 align:middle line:90%


00:11:08.855 --> 00:11:09.355 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:11:09.355 --> 00:11:13.280 align:middle line:90%


00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:15.370 align:middle line:90%
And II is even easier.

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:20.600 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have to show that Y
is a delta D, C, of course,

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:25.210 align:middle line:84%
would be S. So we
have to Y satisfies

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:28.580 align:middle line:84%
the definition of delta-covering
number, so of delta, S set.

00:11:28.580 --> 00:11:33.600 align:middle line:84%
So we intersect with
the ball of radius rho.

00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:36.790 align:middle line:90%


00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:42.490 align:middle line:84%
Well, Y is contained in X. So
this is at most the same thing

00:11:42.490 --> 00:11:46.300 align:middle line:90%
with X instead of rho.

00:11:46.300 --> 00:11:49.190 align:middle line:90%
But X is a delta S, C set.

00:11:49.190 --> 00:11:54.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is at most
C times rho to the S

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:57.430 align:middle line:84%
times the delta-covering
number of X.

00:11:57.430 --> 00:12:00.700 align:middle line:84%
But the delta-covering number
of X is at most K times

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:04.750 align:middle line:84%
by the delta covering
number of Y, by assumption.

00:12:04.750 --> 00:12:10.870 align:middle line:84%
So this is at most CK rho to the
S delta-covering number of Y.

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:18.495 align:middle line:84%
So we have checked that
Y is a delta, S, CK set.

00:12:18.495 --> 00:12:24.088 align:middle line:90%


00:12:24.088 --> 00:12:29.090 align:middle line:84%
So what information have we
gained regarding our task?

00:12:29.090 --> 00:12:32.590 align:middle line:84%
So we need to show that Q of A
contains a delta S plus epsilon

00:12:32.590 --> 00:12:34.400 align:middle line:90%
delta to the minus eta set.

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:37.800 align:middle line:84%
Well if it contains
such a set, then Q of A

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:42.150 align:middle line:84%
must satisfy the conclusion of
the first part of the lemma.

00:12:42.150 --> 00:12:45.570 align:middle line:84%
So the rho-covering number
of Q of A has to be large.

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:48.390 align:middle line:84%
We have proved that the
delta-covering number is large.

00:12:48.390 --> 00:12:50.980 align:middle line:90%


00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:54.180 align:middle line:84%
It is not sufficient, but it is
necessary to show that Q of A

00:12:54.180 --> 00:12:56.730 align:middle line:90%
grows at every scale.

00:12:56.730 --> 00:12:59.070 align:middle line:84%
We want to show that it
contains a delta t over 2

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:02.670 align:middle line:90%
plus epsilon something set.

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:04.535 align:middle line:84%
So it needs to be
large at all scales.

00:13:04.535 --> 00:13:16.660 align:middle line:90%


00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:29.400 align:middle line:84%
So we see that we need Q of A at
scale rho to be larger than rho

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:35.100 align:middle line:84%
to the minus t over 2
minus epsilon for every rho

00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:37.770 align:middle line:84%
between delta and
1 And a priori,

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:39.070 align:middle line:90%
we only know it for delta.

00:13:39.070 --> 00:13:42.020 align:middle line:84%
So what we discussed last time
is that this is true for delta.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:45.900 align:middle line:90%


00:13:45.900 --> 00:13:47.490 align:middle line:84%
And again, this
is not sufficient.

00:13:47.490 --> 00:13:47.990 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:13:47.990 --> 00:13:51.570 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does that say, rho
to the minus S minus epsilon.

00:13:51.570 --> 00:13:53.180 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Rho to the--

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:56.970 align:middle line:84%
so now-- OK, so this was a
general statement about delta S

00:13:56.970 --> 00:13:57.760 align:middle line:90%
sets.

00:13:57.760 --> 00:14:01.260 align:middle line:84%
And now I'm going back to
what we are trying to achieve.

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:03.810 align:middle line:84%
Oh, sorry, S--
yeah, so there is--

00:14:03.810 --> 00:14:04.890 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:14:04.890 --> 00:14:05.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:07.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is still not
Bourgain's projection theorem.

00:14:07.810 --> 00:14:09.880 align:middle line:84%
We are working with
just one setting, 0, 1.

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:10.490 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:14:10.490 --> 00:14:15.580 align:middle line:90%


00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:17.970 align:middle line:90%
We need this to be true.

00:14:17.970 --> 00:14:22.710 align:middle line:84%
And OK, so one we could
think that we have it for

00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:31.560 align:middle line:84%
free because why can't we just
apply what we know at scale rho?

00:14:31.560 --> 00:14:33.510 align:middle line:90%
So this is a question for you.

00:14:33.510 --> 00:14:37.297 align:middle line:84%
So why-- so again,
this is necessary.

00:14:37.297 --> 00:14:38.130 align:middle line:90%
It's not sufficient.

00:14:38.130 --> 00:14:41.710 align:middle line:84%
But OK, let's try to focus
on getting this first.

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:47.550 align:middle line:90%
So why don't we get it for free?

00:14:47.550 --> 00:14:52.320 align:middle line:84%
So what is the difference
between rho and delta?

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:56.430 align:middle line:84%
So that's the assumption
that we have over there.

00:14:56.430 --> 00:14:57.510 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:14:57.510 --> 00:15:03.720 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Because we don't know
that A is rho, S [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:04.870 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Well, OK.

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:07.990 align:middle line:84%
So the assumption is that A
is a delta S something set.

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:09.040 align:middle line:90%
And you're right.

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:13.350 align:middle line:84%
We don't know that A is
a rho S something set.

00:15:13.350 --> 00:15:16.657 align:middle line:84%
There is another thing that
could be a bit worrying--

00:15:16.657 --> 00:15:18.240 align:middle line:84%
I would say it's
less worrying-- which

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:19.657 align:middle line:84%
is that delta to
the minus epsilon

00:15:19.657 --> 00:15:22.075 align:middle line:90%
is not rho to the minus epsilon.

00:15:22.075 --> 00:15:23.700 align:middle line:84%
We would need rho to
the minus epsilon.

00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:25.800 align:middle line:84%
Delta to the minus
epsilon is much bigger.

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:32.201 align:middle line:84%
This last thing is not so
serious because we can always--

00:15:32.201 --> 00:15:33.927 align:middle line:84%
the last thing is
not so serious.

00:15:33.927 --> 00:15:35.760 align:middle line:84%
Neither of them is so
serious in some sense.

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:39.600 align:middle line:84%
But the second one, maybe we'll
come back to discussing later.

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:40.830 align:middle line:90%
But it is less serious.

00:15:40.830 --> 00:15:43.350 align:middle line:90%
The main issue is that--

00:15:43.350 --> 00:15:57.560 align:middle line:84%
so we don't get this for
free, because A needs not

00:15:57.560 --> 00:16:11.240 align:middle line:84%
be a delta rho delta to
the minus epsilon set.

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:14.120 align:middle line:84%
And we also would need
rho here, but let's ignore

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:15.000 align:middle line:90%
this for a moment.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:16.950 align:middle line:90%
And my parameters are all wrong.

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:21.230 align:middle line:84%
Rho S delta to the
minus epsilon set.

00:16:21.230 --> 00:16:24.200 align:middle line:84%
And also, even if
we did, we still

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:27.180 align:middle line:84%
have the issue that this is
necessary but not sufficient.

00:16:27.180 --> 00:16:38.240 align:middle line:90%


00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:41.090 align:middle line:84%
So this condition is
necessary, but not sufficient

00:16:41.090 --> 00:16:44.630 align:middle line:84%
for Q of A to contain
the delta S plus epsilon

00:16:44.630 --> 00:16:48.365 align:middle line:90%
delta to the minus eta set.

00:16:48.365 --> 00:16:49.970 align:middle line:84%
So we are going to
overcome these two

00:16:49.970 --> 00:16:53.070 align:middle line:84%
issues by passing to what
is known as uniform sets.

00:16:53.070 --> 00:16:55.550 align:middle line:84%
So now we make a new
detour, and we are

00:16:55.550 --> 00:16:57.330 align:middle line:90%
going to study uniform sets.

00:16:57.330 --> 00:17:00.350 align:middle line:84%
And so uniform sets
and uniformization

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:03.600 align:middle line:84%
come up all the time in
studying these type of problems,

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:04.859 align:middle line:90%
not only in this proof.

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:08.510 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we will come up
again later in the course.

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:10.640 align:middle line:84%
But it is what we
are going to use

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:12.370 align:middle line:90%
to overcome these two issues.

00:17:12.370 --> 00:17:52.240 align:middle line:90%


00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:55.730 align:middle line:84%
So let's start by defining
what a uniform set is.

00:17:55.730 --> 00:18:04.390 align:middle line:84%
So definition-- so maybe
we've heard definition.

00:18:04.390 --> 00:18:10.210 align:middle line:84%
Let's do some notation so
we can write the definition.

00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:11.840 align:middle line:90%
So this is from last time.

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:16.150 align:middle line:84%
But recall that I was
denoting the delta

00:18:16.150 --> 00:18:18.390 align:middle line:90%
to be the delta mesh cubes.

00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:26.560 align:middle line:90%


00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:32.530 align:middle line:84%
So we split our D into
cubes of side length delta,

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:35.535 align:middle line:84%
and one of them has a
vertex at the origin.

00:18:35.535 --> 00:18:38.540 align:middle line:90%


00:18:38.540 --> 00:18:44.510 align:middle line:84%
So let's define D delta
a set X to be the cubes.

00:18:44.510 --> 00:18:46.420 align:middle line:84%
This is in any dimension,
so the cubes that

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:54.760 align:middle line:84%
are hit by X. So these are the Q
cubes of side length delta which

00:18:54.760 --> 00:19:03.220 align:middle line:90%
hit X.

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:06.520 align:middle line:84%
And let's define a
box-counting version

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:09.770 align:middle line:84%
of a delta-covering
number by looking at this.

00:19:09.770 --> 00:19:16.270 align:middle line:84%
So let's define x delta
star to distinguish it

00:19:16.270 --> 00:19:19.450 align:middle line:84%
from the delta-covering
number to be

00:19:19.450 --> 00:19:20.865 align:middle line:90%
the cardinality of this set.

00:19:20.865 --> 00:19:24.550 align:middle line:90%


00:19:24.550 --> 00:19:27.830 align:middle line:84%
How many delta
cubes the set hits--

00:19:27.830 --> 00:19:32.270 align:middle line:84%
and we discussed last time that
up to a multiplicative constant,

00:19:32.270 --> 00:19:35.180 align:middle line:84%
that could depend on the ambient
dimension, but we don't care.

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:37.850 align:middle line:84%
This is really the same as
the delta-covering number.

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:39.800 align:middle line:84%
So in some sense,
they are the same.

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:43.040 align:middle line:84%
But in order to work
with uniform sets,

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:46.170 align:middle line:84%
this version is
better, as we will see.

00:19:46.170 --> 00:19:50.330 align:middle line:90%


00:19:50.330 --> 00:19:52.900 align:middle line:84%
So we are counting how many
of these are hit by the set X.

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:55.070 align:middle line:84%
And we can compare
cubes with balls.

00:19:55.070 --> 00:19:57.340 align:middle line:84%
And this is why these two
things are comparable,

00:19:57.340 --> 00:20:00.535 align:middle line:90%
as we discussed last time.

00:20:00.535 --> 00:20:05.620 align:middle line:84%
Now we can give a
definition of uniform sets.

00:20:05.620 --> 00:20:07.870 align:middle line:90%
So a set X--

00:20:07.870 --> 00:20:11.380 align:middle line:84%
and now our reference-bounded
part of space is going to be

00:20:11.380 --> 00:20:12.820 align:middle line:90%
the unit ball--

00:20:12.820 --> 00:20:14.200 align:middle line:84%
not the unit ball,
the unit cube.

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:16.040 align:middle line:84%
Not the unit ball,
the unit cube.

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:22.953 align:middle line:84%
So in 0, 1 to the d
is delta m uniform.

00:20:22.953 --> 00:20:26.340 align:middle line:90%


00:20:26.340 --> 00:20:32.200 align:middle line:84%
What is delta is a parameter in
0, 1 So it's a number in 0, 1.

00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:32.940 align:middle line:90%
And what is M?

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:34.085 align:middle line:90%
A natural number.

00:20:34.085 --> 00:20:37.830 align:middle line:90%


00:20:37.830 --> 00:20:39.360 align:middle line:90%
And you should think--

00:20:39.360 --> 00:20:40.990 align:middle line:84%
so I will maybe
come back to this.

00:20:40.990 --> 00:20:44.500 align:middle line:84%
But you should think that
delta is fixed, but M is not.

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:47.027 align:middle line:84%
So we fixed delta and
let M go to infinity,

00:20:47.027 --> 00:20:47.860 align:middle line:90%
something like this.

00:20:47.860 --> 00:20:51.630 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to fix
delta, and then M will grow.

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:54.134 align:middle line:90%
But this is just a definition.

00:20:54.134 --> 00:21:10.740 align:middle line:84%
If the following happens, so for
every J between 0 and M minus 1,

00:21:10.740 --> 00:21:22.950 align:middle line:84%
and for every cube of size delta
to the J that intersects X,

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:28.560 align:middle line:84%
we look at how many cubes of
the next generation hit X.

00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:33.930 align:middle line:84%
And the next generation is
delta to the J plus 1 cubes,

00:21:33.930 --> 00:21:37.870 align:middle line:84%
so for every scale
delta to the J.

00:21:37.870 --> 00:21:40.420 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to look
at scales delta to the J.

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:44.280 align:middle line:84%
For every cube of one of these
scales that intersects the set,

00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:56.850 align:middle line:84%
we look at how
many-- sorry, star--

00:21:56.850 --> 00:22:02.100 align:middle line:84%
how many cubes of the
next-generation scale

00:22:02.100 --> 00:22:07.930 align:middle line:84%
hit X. And this is some number
that depends on the scale J,

00:22:07.930 --> 00:22:10.230 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't depend
on the particular cube

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:20.440 align:middle line:90%
Q. Let's draw a picture.

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:24.020 align:middle line:84%
So this picture's to
understand what's going on.

00:22:24.020 --> 00:22:40.620 align:middle line:90%


00:22:40.620 --> 00:22:42.630 align:middle line:84%
And I guess we
actually want delta

00:22:42.630 --> 00:22:47.530 align:middle line:84%
to be not just a number in 0, 1,
but actually, a dyadic number.

00:22:47.530 --> 00:22:48.430 align:middle line:90%
This is a definition.

00:22:48.430 --> 00:22:50.890 align:middle line:84%
But in practice, we want
to get a dyadic number

00:22:50.890 --> 00:22:52.690 align:middle line:90%
so things are nested.

00:22:52.690 --> 00:22:54.940 align:middle line:84%
So let's draw a picture to
understand what's going on.

00:22:54.940 --> 00:23:01.530 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that delta is 1/2,
and we are in dimension 2.

00:23:01.530 --> 00:23:03.120 align:middle line:90%
So we look at--

00:23:03.120 --> 00:23:05.550 align:middle line:84%
OK, we have a set
X. Let's say that X

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:13.750 align:middle line:84%
hits this 3 dyadic
squares of first level,

00:23:13.750 --> 00:23:15.330 align:middle line:90%
but it doesn't hit this one.

00:23:15.330 --> 00:23:17.635 align:middle line:90%
Then R0 will be 3.

00:23:17.635 --> 00:23:20.930 align:middle line:90%


00:23:20.930 --> 00:23:23.570 align:middle line:84%
There is only one cube
of first level, which

00:23:23.570 --> 00:23:25.910 align:middle line:84%
is the unit cube, by
the assumption that Q

00:23:25.910 --> 00:23:27.300 align:middle line:90%
lives in the unit cube.

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:30.140 align:middle line:84%
So the unit cube has
size delta to the 0.

00:23:30.140 --> 00:23:33.080 align:middle line:84%
And X hits just one
of those because it's

00:23:33.080 --> 00:23:35.330 align:middle line:90%
contained in the unit cube.

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:39.230 align:middle line:84%
Now, we split each of
the surviving squares,

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:42.110 align:middle line:90%
again, dyadically.

00:23:42.110 --> 00:23:45.530 align:middle line:84%
And what uniformity means
is that the number in each

00:23:45.530 --> 00:23:47.330 align:middle line:84%
of these three cubes
that are hit by X

00:23:47.330 --> 00:23:49.003 align:middle line:90%
is the same for all three cubes.

00:23:49.003 --> 00:23:50.670 align:middle line:84%
But the actual cubes
could be different.

00:23:50.670 --> 00:23:55.680 align:middle line:84%
So for example, X could hit
this one, this one, this one,

00:23:55.680 --> 00:23:58.430 align:middle line:84%
this one, this
one, and this one.

00:23:58.430 --> 00:24:00.570 align:middle line:90%
So this is a possibility.

00:24:00.570 --> 00:24:05.270 align:middle line:90%
And in this case, R1 will be 2.

00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:09.020 align:middle line:84%
So every of these
three cubes that

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:13.680 align:middle line:84%
survived in the first
generation hit two cubes

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:15.490 align:middle line:90%
of the second generation.

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:18.570 align:middle line:84%
And what is important is
that it is 2, 2, and 2,

00:24:18.570 --> 00:24:20.440 align:middle line:90%
the same for all the cubes.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:23.430 align:middle line:90%
This is what makes it uniform.

00:24:23.430 --> 00:24:24.430 align:middle line:90%
Now we could keep going.

00:24:24.430 --> 00:24:27.270 align:middle line:84%
So maybe in the next
generation, every one of these

00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:30.330 align:middle line:90%
will hit just one.

00:24:30.330 --> 00:24:32.980 align:middle line:90%
It could be anywhere.

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:35.340 align:middle line:90%
Then R2 would be 1.

00:24:35.340 --> 00:24:38.315 align:middle line:84%
Is it clear what
a uniform set is?

00:24:38.315 --> 00:24:41.290 align:middle line:90%


00:24:41.290 --> 00:24:45.060 align:middle line:84%
So we can see the
set X as a tree

00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:49.420 align:middle line:84%
where the root is the unit cube
the vertices of first level.

00:24:49.420 --> 00:24:53.340 align:middle line:84%
So the children of the unit
cube are the squares of size 1/2

00:24:53.340 --> 00:24:59.500 align:middle line:84%
hitting the set, the
cubes of size 1/2 squared.

00:24:59.500 --> 00:25:03.810 align:middle line:84%
So delta squared will be
the children of the vertices

00:25:03.810 --> 00:25:05.130 align:middle line:90%
of the first level, and so on.

00:25:05.130 --> 00:25:05.630 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:07.005 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How does
this work when

00:25:07.005 --> 00:25:08.730 align:middle line:84%
delta is the reciprocal
of an integer,

00:25:08.730 --> 00:25:10.130 align:middle line:84%
and you have this
kind of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:25:10.130 --> 00:25:12.150 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Otherwise,
things don't line up exactly.

00:25:12.150 --> 00:25:13.400 align:middle line:90%
It's not the end of the world.

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:15.770 align:middle line:84%
But in practice,
we will see that we

00:25:15.770 --> 00:25:17.720 align:middle line:84%
are free to pick delta
satisfying certain--

00:25:17.720 --> 00:25:20.130 align:middle line:84%
well, at this stage,
delta could be anything.

00:25:20.130 --> 00:25:24.470 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, we are going to
pick delta dyadic, not just

00:25:24.470 --> 00:25:27.270 align:middle line:84%
reciprocal of an integer, but
reciprocal of a power of 2,

00:25:27.270 --> 00:25:29.390 align:middle line:90%
just in case.

00:25:29.390 --> 00:25:31.530 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, otherwise, things
are not exactly nested,

00:25:31.530 --> 00:25:33.570 align:middle line:90%
and this picture is not as neat.

00:25:33.570 --> 00:25:37.260 align:middle line:84%
So these numbers are
J. We call them--

00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:39.078 align:middle line:84%
so we can view as a
tree, X as a tree.

00:25:39.078 --> 00:25:41.245 align:middle line:84%
And for this reason, we
call them branching numbers.

00:25:41.245 --> 00:25:59.360 align:middle line:90%


00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:03.050 align:middle line:84%
OK, I'm having a very bad
blackboard management.

00:26:03.050 --> 00:26:06.980 align:middle line:84%
So let's show this
again for a second.

00:26:06.980 --> 00:26:12.700 align:middle line:84%
So in general, if we
have a rho S delta--

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:20.450 align:middle line:84%
sorry, a delta S, C set, it does
not need to be a rho S, C set.

00:26:20.450 --> 00:26:22.460 align:middle line:84%
But if the set is
uniform, it is.

00:26:22.460 --> 00:26:25.940 align:middle line:84%
So this is one big advantage
of working with uniform sets.

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:37.400 align:middle line:84%
So let's say-- so this
will overcome this issue

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:38.930 align:middle line:90%
and also, actually, this issue.

00:26:38.930 --> 00:26:41.740 align:middle line:84%
If the set is uniform,
then this condition

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:49.210 align:middle line:84%
is not only necessary, but
sufficient for the set to be--

00:26:49.210 --> 00:26:52.820 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so if we knew
that Q of A is uniform--

00:26:52.820 --> 00:26:54.920 align:middle line:90%
which we don't, but OK--

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:58.940 align:middle line:84%
we have to work a lot to
actually make this work for us.

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:01.750 align:middle line:84%
But if we have a uniform set,
then both of these issues

00:27:01.750 --> 00:27:02.600 align:middle line:90%
are overcome.

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:07.040 align:middle line:84%
So if the set is uniform,
and it is a delta S, C set,

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:11.170 align:middle line:84%
it is a rho, S,
slightly worse C set.

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:14.920 align:middle line:84%
And if the set satisfies that
it's large at every scale,

00:27:14.920 --> 00:27:19.040 align:middle line:90%
then it is a delta S, C set.

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:21.310 align:middle line:84%
So both of these
issues are overcome

00:27:21.310 --> 00:27:24.910 align:middle line:90%
by working with uniform sets.

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:30.400 align:middle line:90%
OK, let me state how it works.

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:45.315 align:middle line:84%
So let lemma-- so let
X be delta M uniform.

00:27:45.315 --> 00:27:48.790 align:middle line:90%


00:27:48.790 --> 00:27:56.900 align:middle line:84%
And let delta be big delta to
the M. So again, at some point,

00:27:56.900 --> 00:27:58.730 align:middle line:90%
we are going to fix big delta.

00:27:58.730 --> 00:28:01.210 align:middle line:84%
And then this is
not a restriction.

00:28:01.210 --> 00:28:03.220 align:middle line:84%
This is not a
restriction because delta

00:28:03.220 --> 00:28:04.370 align:middle line:90%
will be a constant.

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:07.380 align:middle line:84%
So if delta, small delta,
is not big delta to the M,

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:10.320 align:middle line:84%
we sandwich it between big
delta to the M And big delta

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:13.300 align:middle line:84%
to the M plus 1 and
work with those powers.

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:15.826 align:middle line:84%
So this is not a
big restriction.

00:28:15.826 --> 00:28:18.840 align:middle line:90%


00:28:18.840 --> 00:28:35.940 align:middle line:84%
Then if the size of X is
large, let's say, 1 over C rho

00:28:35.940 --> 00:28:40.110 align:middle line:84%
to the minus S, for every
rho, but in fact, we

00:28:40.110 --> 00:28:41.800 align:middle line:90%
don't even need every rho.

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:46.950 align:middle line:84%
Let's say, for every rho in
1, delta, delta to the M.

00:28:46.950 --> 00:28:50.400 align:middle line:84%
So we only need this to be
true for powers of delta.

00:28:50.400 --> 00:28:53.370 align:middle line:84%
But the point is, if we
know that the size of X

00:28:53.370 --> 00:29:03.930 align:middle line:84%
is large at every scale,
then X is a delta S

00:29:03.930 --> 00:29:06.376 align:middle line:90%
and not quite C set, but--

00:29:06.376 --> 00:29:09.360 align:middle line:90%


00:29:09.360 --> 00:29:12.970 align:middle line:84%
well, up to some constant
that depends on delta.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:16.445 align:middle line:84%
But because delta will be fixed
at some point, this is harmless.

00:29:16.445 --> 00:29:20.100 align:middle line:90%


00:29:20.100 --> 00:29:25.230 align:middle line:84%
So for uniform sets,
it is sufficient to be

00:29:25.230 --> 00:29:30.620 align:middle line:84%
large at all scales for the
set to be a delta S, C set.

00:29:30.620 --> 00:29:36.465 align:middle line:90%


00:29:36.465 --> 00:29:39.493 align:middle line:84%
And what is the other issue that
we wanted to overcome with sets?

00:29:39.493 --> 00:29:42.180 align:middle line:90%


00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:43.545 align:middle line:90%
Oh, OK, and this one, as well.

00:29:43.545 --> 00:29:46.818 align:middle line:90%


00:29:46.818 --> 00:29:51.580 align:middle line:84%
And if X-- so X
is a uniform set.

00:29:51.580 --> 00:30:05.010 align:middle line:84%
If x is a delta S, C set,
then X is a rho, S, and again,

00:30:05.010 --> 00:30:06.870 align:middle line:84%
not quite C, but
we lose something

00:30:06.870 --> 00:30:10.350 align:middle line:84%
that depends on
delta, so we are happy

00:30:10.350 --> 00:30:14.525 align:middle line:84%
set for every rho
between delta and one.

00:30:14.525 --> 00:30:18.540 align:middle line:90%


00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:20.790 align:middle line:84%
Maybe an exercise
for you is to think

00:30:20.790 --> 00:30:24.240 align:middle line:84%
about why both of these
claims are false if we don't

00:30:24.240 --> 00:30:25.840 align:middle line:90%
assume that the set is uniform.

00:30:25.840 --> 00:30:27.220 align:middle line:90%
It does have to be uniform.

00:30:27.220 --> 00:30:30.060 align:middle line:90%
It's not true in general.

00:30:30.060 --> 00:30:33.300 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:34.210 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:30:34.210 --> 00:30:36.690 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I was a
little bit confused.

00:30:36.690 --> 00:30:41.380 align:middle line:84%
If X in a ball that was
covered, like you said,

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:46.210 align:middle line:84%
like [INAUDIBLE] X, it's
not a rho S something set.

00:30:46.210 --> 00:30:48.840 align:middle line:90%


00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:54.240 align:middle line:84%
If X was like rho S
set, why does that

00:30:54.240 --> 00:31:01.670 align:middle line:90%
imply Q X as the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:31:01.670 --> 00:31:03.500 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: OK,
so what we showed

00:31:03.500 --> 00:31:08.330 align:middle line:84%
last time is that, if
A is a delta S, C set,

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:15.770 align:middle line:84%
forget about what is the C, then
Q of A at scale delta grows.

00:31:15.770 --> 00:31:19.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, that is true
for every delta.

00:31:19.670 --> 00:31:25.550 align:middle line:84%
So if the original
A was also a rho,

00:31:25.550 --> 00:31:28.730 align:middle line:84%
S, C set, then we
could apply what

00:31:28.730 --> 00:31:31.550 align:middle line:84%
we did last time with
Rho instead of delta

00:31:31.550 --> 00:31:33.360 align:middle line:90%
and get this conclusion.

00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:41.930 align:middle line:90%


00:31:41.930 --> 00:31:43.790 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It looks
like different rho

00:31:43.790 --> 00:31:48.883 align:middle line:90%
with different polynomial.

00:31:48.883 --> 00:31:50.550 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: The
polynomial is fixed.

00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:52.560 align:middle line:90%
So in the order of quantifiers--

00:31:52.560 --> 00:31:55.410 align:middle line:84%
so maybe this is
still on some board.

00:31:55.410 --> 00:31:56.060 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:56.060 --> 00:31:58.650 align:middle line:84%
You see, the
polynomial comes first.

00:31:58.650 --> 00:31:59.670 align:middle line:90%
The polynomial is fixed.

00:31:59.670 --> 00:32:02.088 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually A,
A, A minus A, A, A.

00:32:02.088 --> 00:32:02.630 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Oh.

00:32:02.630 --> 00:32:04.190 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: The polynomial
doesn't depend on S,

00:32:04.190 --> 00:32:05.700 align:middle line:84%
doesn't depend on rho,
doesn't depend on C.

00:32:05.700 --> 00:32:06.630 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't depend on anything.

00:32:06.630 --> 00:32:08.490 align:middle line:84%
It's a completely
universal polynomial.

00:32:08.490 --> 00:32:10.770 align:middle line:84%
So it's really A,
A, A minus A, A, A.

00:32:10.770 --> 00:32:12.580 align:middle line:90%
Or there are other options.

00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:13.460 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:32:13.460 --> 00:32:14.335 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Yeah.

00:32:14.335 --> 00:32:18.893 align:middle line:90%


00:32:18.893 --> 00:32:19.393 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:19.393 --> 00:32:22.400 align:middle line:90%


00:32:22.400 --> 00:32:24.290 align:middle line:84%
So now we are seeing
both the lemma,

00:32:24.290 --> 00:32:28.100 align:middle line:84%
and you sort of see why
the lemma will be helpful.

00:32:28.100 --> 00:32:29.820 align:middle line:90%
Although, one has to be careful.

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:36.120 align:middle line:84%
And we will be careful because
in order to overcome this,

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:39.960 align:middle line:84%
we need A to be a
rho, S, something set.

00:32:39.960 --> 00:32:43.250 align:middle line:84%
So if A was uniform,
we would be happy.

00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:47.580 align:middle line:84%
But for the second one, we
need Q of A to be uniform--

00:32:47.580 --> 00:32:48.720 align:middle line:90%
not A, but Q of A.

00:32:48.720 --> 00:32:50.990 align:middle line:84%
So to overcome one issue,
we need A to be uniform.

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:53.990 align:middle line:84%
To overcome the other issue,
we need Q of A to be uniform.

00:32:53.990 --> 00:32:56.880 align:middle line:84%
So we still will
have work to do.

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:00.460 align:middle line:84%
But OK, let's go step by step
and let's prove this lemma.

00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:04.130 align:middle line:90%


00:33:04.130 --> 00:33:05.780 align:middle line:84%
And the proof of
the lemma will also

00:33:05.780 --> 00:33:10.165 align:middle line:84%
help us understand and
work with uniform sets.

00:33:10.165 --> 00:33:27.750 align:middle line:90%


00:33:27.750 --> 00:33:30.110 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is to
do everything just

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:32.150 align:middle line:90%
at the scales powers of delta.

00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:35.550 align:middle line:84%
And any other scale we can
sandwich between powers of delta

00:33:35.550 --> 00:33:37.020 align:middle line:90%
because delta is a constant.

00:33:37.020 --> 00:33:41.670 align:middle line:84%
The sandwiching will only lose
a constant depending on delta.

00:33:41.670 --> 00:33:44.250 align:middle line:90%
So for the first--

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:58.390 align:middle line:84%
OK, maybe let's give
it the letters A and B.

00:33:58.390 --> 00:34:04.905 align:middle line:84%
So for A, well, let's consider
rho, some power of delta.

00:34:04.905 --> 00:34:07.750 align:middle line:90%


00:34:07.750 --> 00:34:13.810 align:middle line:84%
Then what is-- so we have to
look at the intersection of A

00:34:13.810 --> 00:34:15.620 align:middle line:90%
with a ball of radius rho.

00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:17.290 align:middle line:84%
But instead of a
ball of radius rho,

00:34:17.290 --> 00:34:19.192 align:middle line:90%
let's use a cube of size rho.

00:34:19.192 --> 00:34:21.400 align:middle line:84%
And again, we can always
pass between cubes and balls

00:34:21.400 --> 00:34:22.630 align:middle line:90%
using only constants.

00:34:22.630 --> 00:34:24.130 align:middle line:84%
And this makes sense
because we want

00:34:24.130 --> 00:34:27.020 align:middle line:84%
to use the assumption
that the set is uniform.

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:35.710 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a Q in delta
D delta to the J of--

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:41.170 align:middle line:84%
I guess I called it X. We
fix one of the scales delta

00:34:41.170 --> 00:34:44.260 align:middle line:84%
to the J. We fix a cube
that intersects the set.

00:34:44.260 --> 00:34:47.469 align:middle line:90%
And what is this?

00:34:47.469 --> 00:34:52.239 align:middle line:90%
Delta is delta to the M.

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:55.270 align:middle line:84%
So here, we are jumping
from scale delta to the J

00:34:55.270 --> 00:34:59.020 align:middle line:84%
to the delta to the M. When we
jump from scale delta to the J

00:34:59.020 --> 00:35:07.150 align:middle line:84%
to delta to the J plus 1,
we have R J plus 1 children.

00:35:07.150 --> 00:35:12.970 align:middle line:84%
Each of those children has
R to the J plus 2 children

00:35:12.970 --> 00:35:18.980 align:middle line:84%
and so on, up to R M
minus 1, with a star.

00:35:18.980 --> 00:35:20.050 align:middle line:90%
So you see what I have.

00:35:20.050 --> 00:35:21.440 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to have this star.

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:24.620 align:middle line:84%
Without the star, this would
be true up to constants.

00:35:24.620 --> 00:35:30.414 align:middle line:90%


00:35:30.414 --> 00:35:36.730 align:middle line:84%
So every time we go down one
scale, every cube splits into R,

00:35:36.730 --> 00:35:39.260 align:middle line:84%
depending on the scale
number of offspring.

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:41.530 align:middle line:84%
And the point is,
it doesn't matter

00:35:41.530 --> 00:35:44.020 align:middle line:84%
where the set is with
the number of offspring

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:48.745 align:middle line:84%
is fixed, but the assumption
that the set is uniform.

00:35:48.745 --> 00:35:57.250 align:middle line:84%
So let's write this as R1, R
M minus 1, divided by R1, RJ.

00:35:57.250 --> 00:36:00.970 align:middle line:90%


00:36:00.970 --> 00:36:02.346 align:middle line:90%
What is the numerator?

00:36:02.346 --> 00:36:09.040 align:middle line:90%


00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:10.160 align:middle line:90%
Sorry 0.

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:10.920 align:middle line:90%
We start at 0.

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:17.620 align:middle line:90%


00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:20.540 align:middle line:90%
What is the numerator?

00:36:20.540 --> 00:36:21.040 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:36:21.040 --> 00:36:23.350 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is it just a
delta-covering number of X?

00:36:23.350 --> 00:36:24.910 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: The delta
are not covering number of X,

00:36:24.910 --> 00:36:26.952 align:middle line:84%
because we start at the
top and we go all the way

00:36:26.952 --> 00:36:28.720 align:middle line:90%
down to the bottom.

00:36:28.720 --> 00:36:34.510 align:middle line:84%
So the numerator is the
delta covering number of A.

00:36:34.510 --> 00:36:36.206 align:middle line:90%
And what is the denominator?

00:36:36.206 --> 00:36:52.620 align:middle line:90%


00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:55.590 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, actually, we
start at J because

00:36:55.590 --> 00:36:57.010 align:middle line:90%
of the way we define things.

00:36:57.010 --> 00:36:58.950 align:middle line:90%
So we stop at J minus 1.

00:36:58.950 --> 00:37:03.325 align:middle line:84%
So J, J plus 1, I
think, now is correct.

00:37:03.325 --> 00:37:03.825 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:37:03.825 --> 00:37:08.100 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is the denominator
just a capital delta to the J

00:37:08.100 --> 00:37:09.210 align:middle line:90%
covering of A?

00:37:09.210 --> 00:37:10.210 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Exactly.

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:14.710 align:middle line:84%
This is the delta to
the J covering number,

00:37:14.710 --> 00:37:17.940 align:middle line:90%
I guess with star--

00:37:17.940 --> 00:37:23.200 align:middle line:84%
because we split into R0
children, then R1 and so on.

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:26.190 align:middle line:84%
And if we stop here, we
stopped at the scale delta

00:37:26.190 --> 00:37:28.410 align:middle line:90%
to the J, big delta to the J.

00:37:28.410 --> 00:37:30.450 align:middle line:90%
And now we use the assumption.

00:37:30.450 --> 00:37:33.480 align:middle line:84%
In part A, the
assumption is that--

00:37:33.480 --> 00:37:37.200 align:middle line:84%
sorry, I keep switching
around A and X.

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:40.020 align:middle line:84%
The assumption is
that this is large.

00:37:40.020 --> 00:37:41.620 align:middle line:90%
So the fraction is small.

00:37:41.620 --> 00:37:46.652 align:middle line:84%
So the assumption is that, so
this is smaller up to a constant

00:37:46.652 --> 00:37:49.110 align:middle line:84%
because now I'm going to go
back to standard delta-covering

00:37:49.110 --> 00:37:50.640 align:middle line:90%
numbers.

00:37:50.640 --> 00:37:58.250 align:middle line:84%
This is C, rho to the S
delta-covering number of A--

00:37:58.250 --> 00:38:01.410 align:middle line:90%
X, sorry.

00:38:01.410 --> 00:38:04.140 align:middle line:90%
So we are done.

00:38:04.140 --> 00:38:13.960 align:middle line:84%
So we took a cube of size delta
to the J. Sorry, delta to the J.

00:38:13.960 --> 00:38:15.660 align:middle line:90%
So this is rho S.

00:38:15.660 --> 00:38:20.730 align:middle line:84%
So we took a cube of size delta
to the J. So delta to the J

00:38:20.730 --> 00:38:21.970 align:middle line:90%
is our Rho.

00:38:21.970 --> 00:38:25.080 align:middle line:84%
And we show that the
delta-covering number of that

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:32.046 align:middle line:84%
is a constant, rho to the S, and
the delta-covering number of X.

00:38:32.046 --> 00:38:52.770 align:middle line:84%
So this shows X is a delta,
S, C set at scales 1, delta,

00:38:52.770 --> 00:38:55.560 align:middle line:90%
delta to the M.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:39:01.290 align:middle line:84%
So it satisfies the condition
of being a delta S, maybe 0, 1--

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:04.930 align:middle line:84%
sorry, 0 of C, 0 of 1
times C at these scales.

00:39:04.930 --> 00:39:17.555 align:middle line:84%
But then we sandwich a scale rho
in delta 1 between two of these.

00:39:17.555 --> 00:39:25.350 align:middle line:90%


00:39:25.350 --> 00:39:29.460 align:middle line:84%
And we are going to
lose some power of delta

00:39:29.460 --> 00:39:31.350 align:middle line:90%
by the sandwiching.

00:39:31.350 --> 00:39:34.090 align:middle line:84%
We are going to lose a power
of delta in the constant.

00:39:34.090 --> 00:39:37.220 align:middle line:84%
So this is why the constant
in the claim depends on delta.

00:39:37.220 --> 00:39:52.160 align:middle line:90%


00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:54.780 align:middle line:84%
An exercise is to
fill in these details.

00:39:54.780 --> 00:40:00.020 align:middle line:84%
But hopefully, this convinces
you that the claim is true.

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:01.320 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

00:40:01.320 --> 00:40:08.255 align:middle line:90%


00:40:08.255 --> 00:40:10.070 align:middle line:84%
And the second part
of the lemma says

00:40:10.070 --> 00:40:12.320 align:middle line:84%
that, if the original
set was a delta S,

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:18.835 align:middle line:84%
C set, then it is also a
rho, S, slightly worse C set.

00:40:18.835 --> 00:40:25.730 align:middle line:90%


00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:27.025 align:middle line:90%
It is a very similar argument.

00:40:27.025 --> 00:40:43.510 align:middle line:90%


00:40:43.510 --> 00:40:45.570 align:middle line:84%
So it's really
the same argument.

00:40:45.570 --> 00:40:47.780 align:middle line:84%
So we do exactly the
same thing again,

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:51.900 align:middle line:84%
except that now, instead of
delta, we have to write rho.

00:40:51.900 --> 00:40:54.715 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's do it again, but it's
basically the same argument.

00:40:54.715 --> 00:41:10.490 align:middle line:90%


00:41:10.490 --> 00:41:17.810 align:middle line:84%
b, so assume that rho is
delta to the J. Otherwise,

00:41:17.810 --> 00:41:19.060 align:middle line:90%
we sandwich as before.

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:30.860 align:middle line:90%


00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:32.653 align:middle line:90%
Maybe delta to the J 0.

00:41:32.653 --> 00:41:36.200 align:middle line:90%


00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:39.860 align:middle line:84%
And then we have to
look at X intersection--

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:45.610 align:middle line:84%
so now we take a
J which is at most

00:41:45.610 --> 00:41:49.210 align:middle line:84%
J 0 because we have to
see what happens when

00:41:49.210 --> 00:41:52.480 align:middle line:84%
we intersect X with
cubes or balls of size

00:41:52.480 --> 00:41:56.410 align:middle line:90%
larger than rho now.

00:41:56.410 --> 00:42:02.250 align:middle line:84%
And let's pick a cube, well,
of size larger than rho.

00:42:02.250 --> 00:42:06.400 align:middle line:90%


00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:09.820 align:middle line:84%
Then we intersect
X with Q. And now

00:42:09.820 --> 00:42:15.520 align:middle line:84%
we look at the
rho-covering number.

00:42:15.520 --> 00:42:17.900 align:middle line:84%
But it is exactly the
same story as before.

00:42:17.900 --> 00:42:18.980 align:middle line:90%
So what is this?

00:42:18.980 --> 00:42:24.450 align:middle line:84%
This is R J0, blah,
blah, blah, R J minus 1.

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:28.150 align:middle line:90%


00:42:28.150 --> 00:42:33.097 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does it start at
RJ and goes to R J0 minus 1?

00:42:33.097 --> 00:42:33.930 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Yes.

00:42:33.930 --> 00:42:47.800 align:middle line:90%


00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:48.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:48.440 --> 00:42:54.070 align:middle line:90%
And this is R1 R J0 minus 1--

00:42:54.070 --> 00:42:59.205 align:middle line:84%
sorry, R 0, R 0,
R 0 R J minus 1.

00:42:59.205 --> 00:43:01.960 align:middle line:90%


00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:07.960 align:middle line:84%
And this is the covering
number at scale delta

00:43:07.960 --> 00:43:16.960 align:middle line:84%
to the J0 divided by the
delta-covering number at scale

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:26.080 align:middle line:90%
delta to the J.

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:33.940 align:middle line:84%
And because the set is a delta
S, C set, this is at most--

00:43:33.940 --> 00:43:39.010 align:middle line:84%
I'll do a constant because I'm
going to now delete the star.

00:43:39.010 --> 00:43:45.220 align:middle line:90%
This is at most C--

00:43:45.220 --> 00:43:48.370 align:middle line:90%
let's write it like rho to the--

00:43:48.370 --> 00:43:48.870 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:43:48.870 --> 00:44:06.220 align:middle line:90%


00:44:06.220 --> 00:44:07.700 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to do this correctly.

00:44:07.700 --> 00:44:08.690 align:middle line:90%
So what is this.

00:44:08.690 --> 00:44:10.990 align:middle line:84%
So here, we start
at the top and go up

00:44:10.990 --> 00:44:14.240 align:middle line:84%
to scale delta to
the J0, which is rho.

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:22.330 align:middle line:84%
So this is actually A the
original set at scale rho.

00:44:22.330 --> 00:44:23.540 align:middle line:90%
We start at the top.

00:44:23.540 --> 00:44:26.810 align:middle line:84%
We go down to scale
delta to the J0

00:44:26.810 --> 00:44:28.043 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: So is this A or X?

00:44:28.043 --> 00:44:28.960 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Sorry.

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:33.255 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] Sorry about that,
X. I should just call it A

00:44:33.255 --> 00:44:35.460 align:middle line:84%
and then-- but if I call
it in the statement,

00:44:35.460 --> 00:44:37.990 align:middle line:84%
then I will write X. So
it's not going to work.

00:44:37.990 --> 00:44:41.910 align:middle line:84%
It's X. There is just
one set which is X.

00:44:41.910 --> 00:44:47.430 align:middle line:84%
And the denominator is a
delta to the J covering

00:44:47.430 --> 00:44:51.840 align:middle line:84%
number of X. The
numerator I just

00:44:51.840 --> 00:44:56.820 align:middle line:84%
write the rho-covering
number of X without the star.

00:44:56.820 --> 00:44:59.710 align:middle line:84%
And for the denominator,
we use the previous lemma.

00:44:59.710 --> 00:45:04.240 align:middle line:84%
So we previously see I think
it's not in any board anymore.

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:05.370 align:middle line:90%
Or maybe it is.

00:45:05.370 --> 00:45:06.370 align:middle line:90%
It is there.

00:45:06.370 --> 00:45:09.532 align:middle line:84%
We saw that, if
we have a delta S,

00:45:09.532 --> 00:45:12.780 align:middle line:84%
C set, then the
rho-covering number is

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:16.860 align:middle line:84%
at least rho to the
minus S divided by C.

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:18.880 align:middle line:90%
So we use that at this scale.

00:45:18.880 --> 00:45:32.520 align:middle line:90%
So this is our R.

00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:37.200 align:middle line:84%
So this has size R
equals delta to the J.

00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:39.900 align:middle line:90%
So we have shown what we wanted.

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:43.860 align:middle line:84%
So now, if we replace
cubes by balls,

00:45:43.860 --> 00:45:48.090 align:middle line:84%
and we interpolate scales, so
we use just powers of delta,

00:45:48.090 --> 00:45:56.940 align:middle line:84%
we get that X intersection a
ball of radius R rho-covering

00:45:56.940 --> 00:46:01.140 align:middle line:84%
number is at most a constant,
at most a constant that

00:46:01.140 --> 00:46:04.710 align:middle line:84%
depends on delta that
comes from the sandwiching.

00:46:04.710 --> 00:46:07.770 align:middle line:84%
The original constant
that is here.

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:12.510 align:middle line:84%
Then this is actually rho to the
minus S in the denominator, R

00:46:12.510 --> 00:46:14.020 align:middle line:84%
to the minus S in
the denominator.

00:46:14.020 --> 00:46:19.480 align:middle line:84%
So we get R to the S and then
the rho-covering number of X.

00:46:19.480 --> 00:46:25.560 align:middle line:84%
And that's the definition of
being a rho, S, slightly worse C

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:26.060 align:middle line:90%
set.

00:46:26.060 --> 00:46:31.560 align:middle line:90%


00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:32.260 align:middle line:90%
Questions?

00:46:32.260 --> 00:46:38.170 align:middle line:90%


00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:41.530 align:middle line:84%
So we have seen that uniform
sets are much better behaved.

00:46:41.530 --> 00:46:46.990 align:middle line:84%
We can first of all, if it
is a good set of scale delta,

00:46:46.990 --> 00:46:49.060 align:middle line:84%
it is a good set at
coarser scales as well.

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:51.780 align:middle line:84%
And also, it's enough
to know that the set is

00:46:51.780 --> 00:46:55.390 align:middle line:84%
large at all scales to know that
it has this spacing condition.

00:46:55.390 --> 00:46:58.210 align:middle line:90%
So how do we find uniform sets?

00:46:58.210 --> 00:47:01.350 align:middle line:84%
So this is the content
of the next lemma, which

00:47:01.350 --> 00:47:04.110 align:middle line:84%
is simple but
extremely important

00:47:04.110 --> 00:47:06.780 align:middle line:84%
and has lots and
lots of applications

00:47:06.780 --> 00:47:07.640 align:middle line:90%
all over the place--

00:47:07.640 --> 00:47:11.250 align:middle line:90%


00:47:11.250 --> 00:47:13.820 align:middle line:84%
but in particular, for
what we are trying to do.

00:47:13.820 --> 00:47:39.440 align:middle line:90%


00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:39.940 align:middle line:90%
Let.

00:47:39.940 --> 00:47:43.850 align:middle line:90%


00:47:43.850 --> 00:47:50.270 align:middle line:84%
little delta be big delta to the
M. And let X be a subset of 0, 1

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:52.040 align:middle line:90%
to the d.

00:47:52.040 --> 00:47:56.690 align:middle line:84%
So we assume nothing about X.
And what the lemma says is that

00:47:56.690 --> 00:48:01.333 align:middle line:84%
x contains a "dense" which
encodes a uniform subset.

00:48:01.333 --> 00:48:04.742 align:middle line:90%


00:48:04.742 --> 00:48:07.080 align:middle line:90%
So what does "dense" mean?

00:48:07.080 --> 00:48:09.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, it means different
things in different settings,

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:11.900 align:middle line:84%
so I'm going to prove a
slightly more general version.

00:48:11.900 --> 00:48:21.066 align:middle line:84%
So let mu be a subadditive
set function finitely--

00:48:21.066 --> 00:48:29.750 align:middle line:90%


00:48:29.750 --> 00:48:33.350 align:middle line:84%
set function, like a measure,
but the only axiom I assume

00:48:33.350 --> 00:48:35.370 align:middle line:84%
is that mu of a
plus B is less than

00:48:35.370 --> 00:48:39.380 align:middle line:84%
or equal than mu of A plus
mu of B, nothing else.

00:48:39.380 --> 00:48:43.517 align:middle line:84%
And a very good example
to keep in mind,

00:48:43.517 --> 00:48:45.600 align:middle line:84%
which is one of the examples
where this is useful,

00:48:45.600 --> 00:48:48.058 align:middle line:84%
but not the only one-- this is
why I state the more general

00:48:48.058 --> 00:48:48.600 align:middle line:90%
version--

00:48:48.600 --> 00:48:54.650 align:middle line:84%
is that mu of B can be the
delta-covering number of B.

00:48:54.650 --> 00:48:57.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is not a measure,
because it is not additive.

00:48:57.930 --> 00:49:00.930 align:middle line:84%
It is extremely far from
additive, but it is subadditive.

00:49:00.930 --> 00:49:04.180 align:middle line:90%


00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:12.410 align:middle line:84%
Then there exists Y, which
is contained in X, which is--

00:49:12.410 --> 00:49:13.590 align:middle line:90%
well, two things happen.

00:49:13.590 --> 00:49:17.620 align:middle line:84%
One is that Y is
delta M uniform.

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:21.830 align:middle line:90%


00:49:21.830 --> 00:49:26.990 align:middle line:84%
And the second thing is that
Y is large measured by mu.

00:49:26.990 --> 00:49:30.650 align:middle line:84%
Mu of Y is large
compared to what?

00:49:30.650 --> 00:49:32.720 align:middle line:90%
Compared to mu of X.

00:49:32.720 --> 00:49:34.170 align:middle line:90%
So mu of X could be anything.

00:49:34.170 --> 00:49:35.212 align:middle line:90%
We don't know what it is.

00:49:35.212 --> 00:49:36.970 align:middle line:90%
Mu is something very general.

00:49:36.970 --> 00:49:39.000 align:middle line:90%
And we do lose something.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:44.700 align:middle line:84%
We lose something like 2
delta log 1 over big delta 2d.

00:49:44.700 --> 00:49:50.150 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, 2d is the ambient
dimension to the n,

00:49:50.150 --> 00:49:51.130 align:middle line:90%
to the minus n.

00:49:51.130 --> 00:50:00.050 align:middle line:90%


00:50:00.050 --> 00:50:03.570 align:middle line:84%
So here, the point is that
the scale is delta to the M.

00:50:03.570 --> 00:50:06.980 align:middle line:84%
And here, we have log of
1 over delta to the M.

00:50:06.980 --> 00:50:08.850 align:middle line:84%
So we lose something
exponential.

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:14.630 align:middle line:84%
But if delta is small, it's
a very small exponential.

00:50:14.630 --> 00:50:18.410 align:middle line:84%
Maybe let's write it
in this equivalent way.

00:50:18.410 --> 00:50:24.550 align:middle line:84%
This is delta to the
minus sigma M mu of X,

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:34.210 align:middle line:84%
where sigma is logarithm of
2d logarithm of 1 over delta--

00:50:34.210 --> 00:50:37.300 align:middle line:90%
so it's a double log--

00:50:37.300 --> 00:50:39.000 align:middle line:90%
divided by log of 1 over delta.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:42.340 align:middle line:90%


00:50:42.340 --> 00:50:44.330 align:middle line:84%
So if we make
delta small enough,

00:50:44.330 --> 00:50:47.500 align:middle line:84%
we can make sigma,
arbitrarily, close to 0.

00:50:47.500 --> 00:50:49.320 align:middle line:84%
So in practice,
at some point, we

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:52.420 align:middle line:84%
are going to choose this
delta so that this is

00:50:52.420 --> 00:50:54.140 align:middle line:90%
small enough for our purposes.

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:58.280 align:middle line:84%
And from that point on, delta
will be fixed, but M will not.

00:50:58.280 --> 00:50:59.990 align:middle line:90%
So M will go to infinity.

00:50:59.990 --> 00:51:06.520 align:middle line:90%


00:51:06.520 --> 00:51:09.580 align:middle line:90%
Proof of the lemma--

00:51:09.580 --> 00:51:12.850 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Where it says
delta to the minus sigma M,

00:51:12.850 --> 00:51:14.800 align:middle line:84%
is it just delta
to the minus sigma?

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:18.070 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN:
Plus sigma M, sorry.

00:51:18.070 --> 00:51:20.110 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:20.110 --> 00:51:22.370 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so the measure--

00:51:22.370 --> 00:51:24.820 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't have to be a
measure, but the measure of Y

00:51:24.820 --> 00:51:27.910 align:middle line:84%
is not much smaller
than the measure of X.

00:51:27.910 --> 00:51:31.520 align:middle line:84%
But not much smaller depends
on your point of view.

00:51:31.520 --> 00:51:34.370 align:middle line:84%
So we do lose some
exponential thing.

00:51:34.370 --> 00:51:36.790 align:middle line:84%
But the sigma is as
small as you want

00:51:36.790 --> 00:51:39.980 align:middle line:90%
by choosing delta small enough.

00:51:39.980 --> 00:51:40.480 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:51:40.480 --> 00:51:43.660 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So you said, we
fix sigma, that is in delta,

00:51:43.660 --> 00:51:45.400 align:middle line:84%
and then we let
M go to infinity.

00:51:45.400 --> 00:51:47.233 align:middle line:90%
So does that blow up?

00:51:47.233 --> 00:51:48.650 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN:
Yeah, it blows up.

00:51:48.650 --> 00:51:51.530 align:middle line:84%
So it's not a--
yeah, it blows up.

00:51:51.530 --> 00:51:53.480 align:middle line:90%
But it blows up like a power.

00:51:53.480 --> 00:51:55.670 align:middle line:84%
But the power is
arbitrarily small.

00:51:55.670 --> 00:51:56.170 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:51:56.170 --> 00:51:57.460 align:middle line:90%
Ah.

00:51:57.460 --> 00:52:00.790 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, bad day with typos.

00:52:00.790 --> 00:52:03.070 align:middle line:90%
Delta to the sigma.

00:52:03.070 --> 00:52:06.870 align:middle line:84%
So small delta is
big delta to the M.

00:52:06.870 --> 00:52:14.150 align:middle line:84%
So small delta is big
delta to the M. So this--

00:52:14.150 --> 00:52:16.090 align:middle line:90%
OK, sorry about this.

00:52:16.090 --> 00:52:21.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is delta to the
sigma by definition of sigma.

00:52:21.770 --> 00:52:24.390 align:middle line:90%


00:52:24.390 --> 00:52:26.915 align:middle line:84%
And actually, it is
delta to the minus sigma.

00:52:26.915 --> 00:52:28.980 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS] Sorry.

00:52:28.980 --> 00:52:30.640 align:middle line:84%
This is delta to
the minus sigma.

00:52:30.640 --> 00:52:32.860 align:middle line:84%
By definition, this is
the definition of sigma.

00:52:32.860 --> 00:52:36.570 align:middle line:84%
So this is big delta
to the sigma M. Big

00:52:36.570 --> 00:52:39.540 align:middle line:84%
delta to the sigma M is
small delta to the sigma.

00:52:39.540 --> 00:52:42.220 align:middle line:84%
So yes, as M goes to
infinity, delta goes to 0.

00:52:42.220 --> 00:52:46.110 align:middle line:84%
This goes to 0, but it goes to 0
as a power, which is arbitrarily

00:52:46.110 --> 00:52:46.780 align:middle line:90%
small.

00:52:46.780 --> 00:52:49.740 align:middle line:84%
So this is the way we
should think about this.

00:52:49.740 --> 00:52:52.110 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:52:52.110 --> 00:52:55.920 align:middle line:90%
Is it correct now?

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:57.880 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:57.880 --> 00:53:00.930 align:middle line:84%
So the proof is some
clever, clever pigeonholing,

00:53:00.930 --> 00:53:03.750 align:middle line:84%
starting from the
bottom of the tree.

00:53:03.750 --> 00:53:06.905 align:middle line:84%
So the proof is trim the tree
starting from the bottom.

00:53:06.905 --> 00:53:49.200 align:middle line:90%


00:53:49.200 --> 00:53:53.760 align:middle line:84%
So we have this at X,
and let's call it XM.

00:53:53.760 --> 00:53:56.276 align:middle line:90%
And we are going to construct--

00:53:56.276 --> 00:54:00.120 align:middle line:90%


00:54:00.120 --> 00:54:01.790 align:middle line:84%
by pigeonholing
from the bottom, we

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:07.410 align:middle line:84%
are going to construct a
nested sequence of sets

00:54:07.410 --> 00:54:09.580 align:middle line:90%
all the way down to X0.

00:54:09.580 --> 00:54:14.430 align:middle line:84%
And this is going to be our
Y that we are looking for.

00:54:14.430 --> 00:54:15.998 align:middle line:90%
OK, so let's explain.

00:54:15.998 --> 00:54:18.040 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to explain how
to construct XM minus 1,

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:21.480 align:middle line:84%
and then we just continue
the same way by induction.

00:54:21.480 --> 00:54:24.680 align:middle line:84%
So we have XM,
which is X, really.

00:54:24.680 --> 00:54:30.600 align:middle line:90%


00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:34.650 align:middle line:84%
So we have all the
cubes of size delta

00:54:34.650 --> 00:54:37.330 align:middle line:84%
to the M minus 1 that
intersect the set.

00:54:37.330 --> 00:54:39.280 align:middle line:84%
But the branching numbers
could be different.

00:54:39.280 --> 00:54:40.780 align:middle line:84%
So this could be
4, this could be 1,

00:54:40.780 --> 00:54:43.360 align:middle line:90%
this could be 2, 2, and so on.

00:54:43.360 --> 00:54:45.700 align:middle line:84%
And we want we want
them all to be the same.

00:54:45.700 --> 00:54:47.280 align:middle line:84%
So we are just
going to pigeonhole

00:54:47.280 --> 00:54:50.153 align:middle line:90%
the most popular value.

00:54:50.153 --> 00:54:51.570 align:middle line:84%
Because there are
too many values,

00:54:51.570 --> 00:54:53.400 align:middle line:84%
we are going to
do it dyadically.

00:54:53.400 --> 00:54:55.630 align:middle line:90%
So that's basically the proof.

00:54:55.630 --> 00:54:58.170 align:middle line:90%
So let's write it down.

00:54:58.170 --> 00:55:09.590 align:middle line:84%
So let XM minus 1 l be the
union of all the queues

00:55:09.590 --> 00:55:15.740 align:middle line:84%
which are squares
of level M minus 1

00:55:15.740 --> 00:55:21.270 align:middle line:84%
that intersects the original set
such that the branching numbers,

00:55:21.270 --> 00:55:24.440 align:middle line:84%
or the number of
descendants of generation

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:31.250 align:middle line:84%
M, so Q intersection X delta
to the M star covering number

00:55:31.250 --> 00:55:33.655 align:middle line:90%
is roughly 2 to the l.

00:55:33.655 --> 00:55:43.190 align:middle line:90%


00:55:43.190 --> 00:55:45.510 align:middle line:84%
And what are the
possible values of l?

00:55:45.510 --> 00:55:48.170 align:middle line:84%
Well, it could be 0 because
there is at least one--

00:55:48.170 --> 00:55:50.870 align:middle line:84%
because the cube
intersects X, there

00:55:50.870 --> 00:55:52.410 align:middle line:90%
is at least one descendant.

00:55:52.410 --> 00:55:55.200 align:middle line:84%
And the largest it
could possibly be--

00:55:55.200 --> 00:56:02.480 align:middle line:84%
so the largest 2 to the l can
be is delta to the minus D.

00:56:02.480 --> 00:56:05.720 align:middle line:84%
So each time we go
down one generation,

00:56:05.720 --> 00:56:08.480 align:middle line:84%
we subdivide into relative
scale 1 over delta,

00:56:08.480 --> 00:56:10.160 align:middle line:90%
and we have D dimensions.

00:56:10.160 --> 00:56:19.700 align:middle line:84%
So l ranges from 0
to the logarithm of--

00:56:19.700 --> 00:56:22.930 align:middle line:84%
well, D logarithm
of 1 over delta.

00:56:22.930 --> 00:56:26.960 align:middle line:90%


00:56:26.960 --> 00:56:29.010 align:middle line:90%
So we pigeonhole.

00:56:29.010 --> 00:56:29.910 align:middle line:90%
Mu is subadditive.

00:56:29.910 --> 00:56:31.410 align:middle line:84%
So you see that
this is what we use.

00:56:31.410 --> 00:56:33.780 align:middle line:90%
So mu of X is this.

00:56:33.780 --> 00:56:36.170 align:middle line:90%
These sets cover X.

00:56:36.170 --> 00:56:42.440 align:middle line:84%
So mu of X is at most
the sum over l of mu XM.

00:56:42.440 --> 00:56:45.120 align:middle line:84%
So it is X, but
let's write it as XM

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:50.660 align:middle line:84%
so it's clear how to continue
inductively, X minus 1 l,

00:56:50.660 --> 00:56:56.180 align:middle line:84%
and l takes D log 1 over
delta possible values.

00:56:56.180 --> 00:57:07.610 align:middle line:84%
So there exists some l such that
mu of x minus 1 l has measured

00:57:07.610 --> 00:57:10.710 align:middle line:84%
at least-- maybe let's
put a tilde just in case--

00:57:10.710 --> 00:57:21.590 align:middle line:84%
1 over the log of 1 over
delta times the measure of X.

00:57:21.590 --> 00:57:23.205 align:middle line:90%
And so what the situation now?

00:57:23.205 --> 00:57:25.220 align:middle line:84%
Now we know that the
number of offspring

00:57:25.220 --> 00:57:27.480 align:middle line:90%
is constant up to a factor of 2.

00:57:27.480 --> 00:57:28.863 align:middle line:90%
So here there could be 7.

00:57:28.863 --> 00:57:29.780 align:middle line:90%
Here there could be 8.

00:57:29.780 --> 00:57:31.310 align:middle line:90%
Here there could be five.

00:57:31.310 --> 00:57:34.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, in that case, we are going
to keep the 4 with the largest

00:57:34.430 --> 00:57:38.500 align:middle line:84%
mass, which, again, we can
do by subadditivity of mu.

00:57:38.500 --> 00:57:41.300 align:middle line:90%


00:57:41.300 --> 00:57:54.540 align:middle line:84%
So inside each Q which
is a subset of these,

00:57:54.540 --> 00:58:02.843 align:middle line:84%
so the ones that survived,
keep 2 to the l cubes--

00:58:02.843 --> 00:58:06.550 align:middle line:90%


00:58:06.550 --> 00:58:07.490 align:middle line:90%
exactly 2 to the l.

00:58:07.490 --> 00:58:09.740 align:middle line:84%
So there are between 2 to
the l and 2 to the l plus 1.

00:58:09.740 --> 00:58:15.820 align:middle line:84%
We give exactly 2 to the l
cubes of size delta to the M.

00:58:15.820 --> 00:58:18.500 align:middle line:84%
By doing this, we lose
another factor of 2.

00:58:18.500 --> 00:58:21.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is why we have
2d log of 1 over delta.

00:58:21.530 --> 00:58:24.345 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it should be 4
or something like this.

00:58:24.345 --> 00:58:25.720 align:middle line:84%
But of course, it
doesn't matter.

00:58:25.720 --> 00:58:28.930 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.930 --> 00:58:34.170 align:middle line:84%
Let X M minus 1 be the
union of all of those.

00:58:34.170 --> 00:58:39.175 align:middle line:90%


00:58:39.175 --> 00:58:41.670 align:middle line:84%
So first, we do
dyadic pigeonholing

00:58:41.670 --> 00:58:43.420 align:middle line:84%
because in dyadic
pigeonholing, things are

00:58:43.420 --> 00:58:44.990 align:middle line:90%
constant up to a factor of 2.

00:58:44.990 --> 00:58:47.300 align:middle line:84%
Then I trim again to
make it exactly constant.

00:58:47.300 --> 00:58:49.390 align:middle line:90%
Then I only lose a factor of 2.

00:58:49.390 --> 00:58:56.980 align:middle line:84%
So by doing this, now we
have our set X M minus 1.

00:58:56.980 --> 00:59:00.637 align:middle line:84%
And the size-- sorry, the
size in terms of the measure.

00:59:00.637 --> 00:59:02.720 align:middle line:84%
So the measure could be
the delta-covering number,

00:59:02.720 --> 00:59:03.928 align:middle line:90%
but it could be other things.

00:59:03.928 --> 00:59:11.270 align:middle line:84%
So the measure of X M minus 1 is
bigger than 1 over to the log 1

00:59:11.270 --> 00:59:17.620 align:middle line:84%
over delta times the
measure of X and D

00:59:17.620 --> 00:59:20.090 align:middle line:84%
set is now uniform
at the last scale.

00:59:20.090 --> 00:59:35.600 align:middle line:84%
So every Q that intersects this
new set has some fixed number--

00:59:35.600 --> 00:59:39.590 align:middle line:84%
let's call it R minus
1-- descendants.

00:59:39.590 --> 00:59:46.900 align:middle line:90%


00:59:46.900 --> 00:59:50.900 align:middle line:84%
So this will be 2 to the l
for the l that we pigeonholed.

00:59:50.900 --> 00:59:54.910 align:middle line:90%


00:59:54.910 --> 00:59:56.890 align:middle line:84%
And now we take X
M minus 1, and we

00:59:56.890 --> 01:00:02.480 align:middle line:84%
keep going up until all the way
up to the top, until we get X0.

01:00:02.480 --> 01:00:05.985 align:middle line:84%
And then we have to convince
ourselves that X 0 works.

01:00:05.985 --> 01:00:30.910 align:middle line:90%


01:00:30.910 --> 01:00:33.650 align:middle line:90%
OK, so one thing is clear.

01:00:33.650 --> 01:00:36.320 align:middle line:84%
Every time we iterate,
we lose this factor.

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:38.690 align:middle line:90%
So we lose this factor M times.

01:00:38.690 --> 01:00:42.375 align:middle line:84%
And that was the second
part of the claim.

01:00:42.375 --> 01:00:58.380 align:middle line:90%


01:00:58.380 --> 01:01:02.820 align:middle line:84%
And the second claim is
that the set Y is uniform.

01:01:02.820 --> 01:01:08.370 align:middle line:84%
Well, every time we
do this, it becomes

01:01:08.370 --> 01:01:10.900 align:middle line:84%
uniform from one
scale to the next.

01:01:10.900 --> 01:01:12.930 align:middle line:84%
And the only thing that
needs to be observed

01:01:12.930 --> 01:01:14.170 align:middle line:90%
is that this is preserved.

01:01:14.170 --> 01:01:18.910 align:middle line:84%
So when we go up from scale
M minus 1 to scale M minus 2,

01:01:18.910 --> 01:01:21.730 align:middle line:84%
we don't mess up the
uniformity that we already had.

01:01:21.730 --> 01:01:23.945 align:middle line:84%
And let me do a
proof by picture.

01:01:23.945 --> 01:01:30.300 align:middle line:90%


01:01:30.300 --> 01:01:32.160 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that, in
the first stage,

01:01:32.160 --> 01:01:36.780 align:middle line:90%
we chose these three cubes.

01:01:36.780 --> 01:01:40.950 align:middle line:84%
And each of them has the
same number of descendants.

01:01:40.950 --> 01:01:45.090 align:middle line:84%
In the next stage, we
might remove some of these.

01:01:45.090 --> 01:01:46.773 align:middle line:90%
But it doesn't matter.

01:01:46.773 --> 01:01:48.940 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that we remove
this one in the next stage.

01:01:48.940 --> 01:01:51.370 align:middle line:84%
So the ones we keep still
have the uniformity.

01:01:51.370 --> 01:01:53.040 align:middle line:84%
So we don't destroy
the uniformity

01:01:53.040 --> 01:01:55.920 align:middle line:84%
that we already obtained
at finer scale scales

01:01:55.920 --> 01:01:57.520 align:middle line:90%
when we go to coarser scales.

01:01:57.520 --> 01:01:58.505 align:middle line:90%
So it is uniform.

01:01:58.505 --> 01:02:07.010 align:middle line:90%


01:02:07.010 --> 01:02:13.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is the proof
that, given any set,

01:02:13.770 --> 01:02:17.940 align:middle line:84%
we can find a dense in this set,
dense up to delta to the sigma

01:02:17.940 --> 01:02:19.870 align:middle line:90%
such that it is also uniform.

01:02:19.870 --> 01:02:23.170 align:middle line:84%
And well, by taking mu to be
the delta-covering number,

01:02:23.170 --> 01:02:25.780 align:middle line:84%
it is literally dense
in the standard way.

01:02:25.780 --> 01:02:29.650 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes it's convenient,
as we will see or maybe not,

01:02:29.650 --> 01:02:31.050 align:middle line:90%
depending on time.

01:02:31.050 --> 01:02:32.830 align:middle line:84%
It is convenient
to take other mu's.

01:02:32.830 --> 01:02:36.960 align:middle line:84%
This is why I stated
it in this way.

01:02:36.960 --> 01:02:38.683 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

01:02:38.683 --> 01:02:41.100 align:middle line:84%
Again, all of the tools that
we have been discussing today

01:02:41.100 --> 01:02:42.790 align:middle line:84%
are useful not
just in this proof,

01:02:42.790 --> 01:02:45.010 align:middle line:84%
but all over the place
in projection theory.

01:02:45.010 --> 01:02:45.610 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:02:45.610 --> 01:02:48.810 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I'm a bit confused
by this construction.

01:02:48.810 --> 01:02:57.740 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I [INAUDIBLE] on
