01:04:03.980 --> 01:04:04.520 align:middle line:90%
Thanks.

01:04:04.520 --> 01:04:05.478 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Mm-hmm.

01:04:05.478 --> 01:04:08.770 align:middle line:90%


01:04:08.770 --> 01:04:12.260 align:middle line:84%
So in the remaining
14 minutes, let's

01:04:12.260 --> 01:04:14.390 align:middle line:84%
try to go back and
see how all of this

01:04:14.390 --> 01:04:17.155 align:middle line:84%
helps us deal with
the issue that we had.

01:04:17.155 --> 01:04:32.690 align:middle line:90%


01:04:32.690 --> 01:05:06.650 align:middle line:90%
Maybe let's keep the lemma

01:05:06.650 --> 01:05:07.860 align:middle line:90%
So let's go back.

01:05:07.860 --> 01:05:09.520 align:middle line:90%
So now we go back to our goal.

01:05:09.520 --> 01:05:16.850 align:middle line:90%


01:05:16.850 --> 01:05:25.980 align:middle line:84%
So A is a delta S. So this
C is delta to the minus eta.

01:05:25.980 --> 01:05:28.648 align:middle line:84%
But that's not where
the issue lies.

01:05:28.648 --> 01:05:31.190 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, if you want
to write the things correctly,

01:05:31.190 --> 01:05:33.900 align:middle line:84%
you have to keep track of many
parameters and how they change.

01:05:33.900 --> 01:05:36.150 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not going to be
able to do that today,

01:05:36.150 --> 01:05:37.480 align:middle line:90%
so let's ignore this.

01:05:37.480 --> 01:05:41.030 align:middle line:90%


01:05:41.030 --> 01:05:46.675 align:middle line:84%
So we know that Q of A has
large size at scale delta.

01:05:46.675 --> 01:05:53.260 align:middle line:90%


01:05:53.260 --> 01:05:59.740 align:middle line:84%
So the first thing we do
is we replace-- so Q of A

01:05:59.740 --> 01:06:03.340 align:middle line:84%
is A, A, A minus A,
A, A. So by using

01:06:03.340 --> 01:06:05.560 align:middle line:84%
similar techniques or
basically the same techniques

01:06:05.560 --> 01:06:08.950 align:middle line:84%
that you are already used
in the finite field setting,

01:06:08.950 --> 01:06:11.180 align:middle line:84%
we can get the
following conclusion.

01:06:11.180 --> 01:06:17.093 align:middle line:84%
There exists one A in A, such
that A plus little A, A grows.

01:06:17.093 --> 01:06:20.395 align:middle line:90%


01:06:20.395 --> 01:06:21.532 align:middle line:90%
It's not the same epsilon.

01:06:21.532 --> 01:06:23.865 align:middle line:84%
So every time I write epsilon,
it's a different epsilon.

01:06:23.865 --> 01:06:26.440 align:middle line:90%


01:06:26.440 --> 01:06:31.300 align:middle line:84%
Is that OK, or do you want
me to write the epsilon 1?

01:06:31.300 --> 01:06:32.270 align:middle line:90%
We lose a lot.

01:06:32.270 --> 01:06:35.390 align:middle line:90%
So this epsilon, we lose a lot.

01:06:35.390 --> 01:06:37.940 align:middle line:84%
So this is similar to
the finite field setting.

01:06:37.940 --> 01:06:42.730 align:middle line:84%
This uses a Ruzsa's
triangle inequality.

01:06:42.730 --> 01:06:45.580 align:middle line:84%
I guess the main thing it
uses is Plünnecke-Ruzsa.

01:06:45.580 --> 01:06:47.860 align:middle line:84%
And as I explained last
time, all of these things

01:06:47.860 --> 01:06:50.770 align:middle line:84%
are still true for
delta-covering numbers.

01:06:50.770 --> 01:06:57.400 align:middle line:84%
So uses Plünnecke-Ruzsa,
Ruzsa's triangle inequality,

01:06:57.400 --> 01:07:01.000 align:middle line:84%
and I guess, maybe
some double counting.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:02.660 align:middle line:84%
So I'm not saying
this is trivial,

01:07:02.660 --> 01:07:06.790 align:middle line:84%
but I hope you did something
similar in the finite field

01:07:06.790 --> 01:07:08.380 align:middle line:90%
setting.

01:07:08.380 --> 01:07:09.440 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

01:07:09.440 --> 01:07:16.904 align:middle line:90%


01:07:16.904 --> 01:07:19.425 align:middle line:84%
Second, we can assume
that a is uniform.

01:07:19.425 --> 01:07:22.580 align:middle line:90%


01:07:22.580 --> 01:07:24.980 align:middle line:84%
So first, we assume
that A is uniform.

01:07:24.980 --> 01:07:26.600 align:middle line:90%
And second, we do this.

01:07:26.600 --> 01:07:27.620 align:middle line:90%
Maybe this is better.

01:07:27.620 --> 01:07:29.373 align:middle line:90%
So A is uniform.

01:07:29.373 --> 01:07:34.010 align:middle line:90%


01:07:34.010 --> 01:07:38.415 align:middle line:84%
So we have to choose, at this
stage, delta small enough.

01:07:38.415 --> 01:07:44.930 align:middle line:90%


01:07:44.930 --> 01:07:50.920 align:middle line:84%
So here, the mu is just
the delta-covering number.

01:07:50.920 --> 01:07:53.890 align:middle line:84%
So we apply the
uniformization lemma.

01:07:53.890 --> 01:07:57.040 align:middle line:84%
So we start with
the delta S, C set.

01:07:57.040 --> 01:07:59.060 align:middle line:90%
Now we pass to a uniform subset.

01:07:59.060 --> 01:08:01.870 align:middle line:84%
The uniform subset is
dense up to a factor delta

01:08:01.870 --> 01:08:02.987 align:middle line:90%
to the epsilon--

01:08:02.987 --> 01:08:04.570 align:middle line:84%
not epsilon, delta
to the sigma, where

01:08:04.570 --> 01:08:06.640 align:middle line:90%
sigma is as small as I want.

01:08:06.640 --> 01:08:09.670 align:middle line:84%
Then subsets of delta,
S sets are still

01:08:09.670 --> 01:08:12.800 align:middle line:84%
delta, S sets by the
lemma that we saw before.

01:08:12.800 --> 01:08:14.240 align:middle line:90%
This is why we can assume this.

01:08:14.240 --> 01:08:16.810 align:middle line:84%
Now, this constant
is going to become

01:08:16.810 --> 01:08:20.140 align:middle line:84%
worse by a factor of
delta to the minus sigma

01:08:20.140 --> 01:08:22.210 align:middle line:90%
because that's the density.

01:08:22.210 --> 01:08:30.020 align:middle line:84%
So C gets worse by delta
to the minus sigma.

01:08:30.020 --> 01:08:31.935 align:middle line:90%
But sigma is arbitrarily small.

01:08:31.935 --> 01:08:35.109 align:middle line:90%


01:08:35.109 --> 01:08:37.779 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to ignore it.

01:08:37.779 --> 01:08:40.460 align:middle line:84%
So you have to keep track
of all of these parameters.

01:08:40.460 --> 01:08:42.200 align:middle line:90%
But they are not the real issue.

01:08:42.200 --> 01:08:43.617 align:middle line:84%
You have to be
careful about that.

01:08:43.617 --> 01:08:45.138 align:middle line:90%
They are not the real issue.

01:08:45.138 --> 01:08:48.090 align:middle line:84%
Then, this A still
satisfies the assumptions

01:08:48.090 --> 01:08:49.359 align:middle line:90%
of what we did last time.

01:08:49.359 --> 01:08:50.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is really
the first step.

01:08:50.950 --> 01:08:54.680 align:middle line:84%
And so we know that a for the
uniform one A, A, A minus A,

01:08:54.680 --> 01:08:55.750 align:middle line:90%
A, A grows.

01:08:55.750 --> 01:08:57.380 align:middle line:90%
So already, this grows.

01:08:57.380 --> 01:09:02.941 align:middle line:90%


01:09:02.941 --> 01:09:04.210 align:middle line:90%
But A is uniform.

01:09:04.210 --> 01:09:09.810 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, because
A is uniform,

01:09:09.810 --> 01:09:11.678 align:middle line:84%
by the lemma that we
used about uniformity,

01:09:11.678 --> 01:09:12.845 align:middle line:90%
this is true at every scale.

01:09:12.845 --> 01:09:33.212 align:middle line:90%


01:09:33.212 --> 01:09:34.879 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, we have
this at every scale.

01:09:34.879 --> 01:09:39.510 align:middle line:90%


01:09:39.510 --> 01:09:44.279 align:middle line:84%
The third thing that is going to
be important is that, a priori,

01:09:44.279 --> 01:09:47.460 align:middle line:84%
we only have one A
in A. But in fact,

01:09:47.460 --> 01:09:51.420 align:middle line:84%
once we have it for 1A in we
have it for almost all in a.

01:09:51.420 --> 01:09:55.620 align:middle line:84%
And maybe you have seen
this sort of argument

01:09:55.620 --> 01:09:57.040 align:middle line:90%
in the finite field setting.

01:09:57.040 --> 01:10:05.730 align:middle line:84%
but this is true for
almost all a and A

01:10:05.730 --> 01:10:13.800 align:middle line:84%
because we define A bad
to be the points in A such

01:10:13.800 --> 01:10:15.340 align:middle line:90%
that the conclusion we want--

01:10:15.340 --> 01:10:18.090 align:middle line:90%
so the second step is not true.

01:10:18.090 --> 01:10:18.905 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't hold.

01:10:18.905 --> 01:10:23.250 align:middle line:90%


01:10:23.250 --> 01:10:26.640 align:middle line:84%
And if the set is large, we
can apply the same argument

01:10:26.640 --> 01:10:28.600 align:middle line:84%
to this set and get
a contradiction.

01:10:28.600 --> 01:10:40.590 align:middle line:90%


01:10:40.590 --> 01:10:43.200 align:middle line:84%
So a dense subset
of a delta S, C set

01:10:43.200 --> 01:10:45.820 align:middle line:84%
is a delta S,
slightly worse C set.

01:10:45.820 --> 01:10:49.270 align:middle line:84%
How much worse a constant is
depends on how dense A bad is.

01:10:49.270 --> 01:10:52.030 align:middle line:84%
So if A bad is too dense,
we get a contradiction.

01:10:52.030 --> 01:10:53.410 align:middle line:90%
So it cannot be too dense.

01:10:53.410 --> 01:10:59.250 align:middle line:84%
And this means that
very few A's are bad.

01:10:59.250 --> 01:11:00.800 align:middle line:90%
So almost all A are not bad.

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:10.560 align:middle line:90%


01:11:10.560 --> 01:11:17.650 align:middle line:84%
Well, the step just 2 to A bad,
and we get a contradiction.

01:11:17.650 --> 01:11:50.800 align:middle line:90%


01:11:50.800 --> 01:11:53.850 align:middle line:84%
The first step is
maybe the key step.

01:11:53.850 --> 01:11:57.140 align:middle line:84%
So we are going to
upgrade the second step

01:11:57.140 --> 01:12:01.100 align:middle line:84%
to not just saying that A plus
little A, A is large, but--

01:12:01.100 --> 01:12:02.900 align:middle line:90%
so what is A plus little A, A?

01:12:02.900 --> 01:12:05.480 align:middle line:84%
It's pi A of A
times A. So we are

01:12:05.480 --> 01:12:08.540 align:middle line:84%
going to upgrade this to
say that this is still true

01:12:08.540 --> 01:12:11.810 align:middle line:84%
if we pass to a dense
subset of A times A.

01:12:11.810 --> 01:12:21.680 align:middle line:84%
So first step, if X is contained
in A plus A, and it is dense,

01:12:21.680 --> 01:12:27.260 align:middle line:84%
in the sense that the delta
covering number doesn't--

01:12:27.260 --> 01:12:29.780 align:middle line:84%
so at some point, there
should be a parameter eta

01:12:29.780 --> 01:12:31.440 align:middle line:90%
that I am completely ignoring.

01:12:31.440 --> 01:12:34.653 align:middle line:84%
Maybe at this step, we want
something like eta square dense.

01:12:34.653 --> 01:12:40.280 align:middle line:90%


01:12:40.280 --> 01:12:44.440 align:middle line:84%
Then if we project X,
we still have growth.

01:12:44.440 --> 01:12:47.930 align:middle line:90%


01:12:47.930 --> 01:12:52.460 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, at all scales,
or almost all scales.

01:12:52.460 --> 01:12:56.040 align:middle line:84%
Maybe instead of epsilon, the
growth will be epsilon over 2.

01:12:56.040 --> 01:12:59.580 align:middle line:90%
But there will still be growth.

01:12:59.580 --> 01:13:01.040 align:middle line:90%
Let me try to explain.

01:13:01.040 --> 01:13:03.780 align:middle line:84%
The first step in the
last five minutes.

01:13:03.780 --> 01:13:08.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is really, as we will
see, the absolutely key step.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:12.530 align:middle line:84%
We need to make this estimate in
the second step robust underpass

01:13:12.530 --> 01:13:13.800 align:middle line:90%
into dense subsets.

01:13:13.800 --> 01:13:16.220 align:middle line:84%
And we will see,
maybe next time,

01:13:16.220 --> 01:13:18.770 align:middle line:84%
why this is what we
really need to do in order

01:13:18.770 --> 01:13:20.270 align:middle line:90%
to conclude what we want.

01:13:20.270 --> 01:13:24.320 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that one is
in A, and this is just

01:13:24.320 --> 01:13:25.996 align:middle line:90%
for notational simplicity.

01:13:25.996 --> 01:13:40.070 align:middle line:90%


01:13:40.070 --> 01:13:41.630 align:middle line:90%
So there are two possibilities.

01:13:41.630 --> 01:13:47.320 align:middle line:84%
One-- OK, so we want
to show that there

01:13:47.320 --> 01:13:52.570 align:middle line:84%
exists an A with this property,
one a in A with this property.

01:13:52.570 --> 01:13:56.332 align:middle line:84%
I guess step 3 should
maybe be a later step.

01:13:56.332 --> 01:13:58.763 align:middle line:84%
Or maybe we want to
apply it at many steps.

01:13:58.763 --> 01:14:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So many steps, we prove
that something exists.

01:14:00.680 --> 01:14:03.550 align:middle line:84%
But once something exists,
actually, almost all elements

01:14:03.550 --> 01:14:05.120 align:middle line:90%
in A have this property.

01:14:05.120 --> 01:14:06.670 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's say we
want to prove that--

01:14:06.670 --> 01:14:09.580 align:middle line:84%
So at this stage we want
to get one in little A in A

01:14:09.580 --> 01:14:11.290 align:middle line:90%
so that this is true.

01:14:11.290 --> 01:14:13.820 align:middle line:90%
So maybe we are lucky.

01:14:13.820 --> 01:14:15.400 align:middle line:90%
And the first thing we choose--

01:14:15.400 --> 01:14:17.290 align:middle line:90%
and let's call it 1-- works.

01:14:17.290 --> 01:14:19.780 align:middle line:90%
Well, if it works, it works.

01:14:19.780 --> 01:14:21.135 align:middle line:90%
So first case--

01:14:21.135 --> 01:14:24.430 align:middle line:90%


01:14:24.430 --> 01:14:27.130 align:middle line:90%
A equals 1 works.

01:14:27.130 --> 01:14:29.680 align:middle line:90%
So it has this property.

01:14:29.680 --> 01:14:31.190 align:middle line:90%
Well, if it works, it works.

01:14:31.190 --> 01:14:31.960 align:middle line:90%
We are done.

01:14:31.960 --> 01:14:34.380 align:middle line:84%
So let's assume
that 1 doesn't work.

01:14:34.380 --> 01:14:43.780 align:middle line:90%


01:14:43.780 --> 01:14:46.250 align:middle line:84%
What does it mean that
A equals 1 doesn't work?

01:14:46.250 --> 01:14:51.520 align:middle line:84%
It means that there exists
some X in A times A which

01:14:51.520 --> 01:14:56.360 align:middle line:84%
has size bigger than
delta to the eta squared

01:14:56.360 --> 01:15:00.490 align:middle line:84%
or something like this times
the size of eta times A.

01:15:00.490 --> 01:15:02.475 align:middle line:90%
But the projection is small.

01:15:02.475 --> 01:15:06.415 align:middle line:90%


01:15:06.415 --> 01:15:08.360 align:middle line:84%
We have to do this
for every rho.

01:15:08.360 --> 01:15:12.820 align:middle line:84%
But let's do it one rho at a
time, and next time, I will--

01:15:12.820 --> 01:15:13.880 align:middle line:90%
let's do it for delta.

01:15:13.880 --> 01:15:17.620 align:middle line:84%
Next time, I will explain why
it's true for every delta,

01:15:17.620 --> 01:15:20.290 align:middle line:90%
in some sense.

01:15:20.290 --> 01:15:23.950 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's assume that, for
the particular scale delta,

01:15:23.950 --> 01:15:25.830 align:middle line:90%
there is no growth.

01:15:25.830 --> 01:15:28.840 align:middle line:90%


01:15:28.840 --> 01:15:33.280 align:middle line:90%
Well, this reminds you of what?

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:34.660 align:middle line:84%
So there is a
theorem that you've

01:15:34.660 --> 01:15:36.420 align:middle line:84%
seen before that
should remind you of.

01:15:36.420 --> 01:15:43.630 align:middle line:90%


01:15:43.630 --> 01:15:45.910 align:middle line:90%
So we are projecting--

01:15:45.910 --> 01:15:47.510 align:middle line:90%
sorry, an A is 1.

01:15:47.510 --> 01:15:48.290 align:middle line:90%
Actually, A is 1.

01:15:48.290 --> 01:15:50.740 align:middle line:90%
So this is just the sum.

01:15:50.740 --> 01:15:53.115 align:middle line:90%
So we are-- so if 1--

01:15:53.115 --> 01:15:55.490 align:middle line:84%
we assume one is in A. Either
it is good-- if it is good,

01:15:55.490 --> 01:15:56.980 align:middle line:84%
we have proved what we want
because something is good,

01:15:56.980 --> 01:15:57.730 align:middle line:90%
or it's not good.

01:15:57.730 --> 01:16:01.390 align:middle line:84%
If it's not good, this is
what it means, by definition

01:16:01.390 --> 01:16:04.720 align:middle line:90%
of not being good.

01:16:04.720 --> 01:16:09.100 align:middle line:84%
B is G. So this is
exactly the assumption

01:16:09.100 --> 01:16:12.310 align:middle line:90%
to apply Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers.

01:16:12.310 --> 01:16:16.930 align:middle line:84%
So A has size delta
to the minus S.

01:16:16.930 --> 01:16:21.460 align:middle line:84%
Here we have a dense
subset of the product set

01:16:21.460 --> 01:16:23.920 align:middle line:90%
which has small partial sum set.

01:16:23.920 --> 01:16:25.790 align:middle line:90%
The pi 1 image is small.

01:16:25.790 --> 01:16:27.150 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't grow.

01:16:27.150 --> 01:16:28.950 align:middle line:84%
So these are exactly
the assumptions

01:16:28.950 --> 01:16:31.390 align:middle line:84%
that we need to apply
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers.

01:16:31.390 --> 01:16:42.570 align:middle line:90%


01:16:42.570 --> 01:16:43.540 align:middle line:90%
I've run out of time.

01:16:43.540 --> 01:16:47.620 align:middle line:84%
So we are in the middle of
the most important argument.

01:16:47.620 --> 01:16:51.700 align:middle line:84%
So maybe on Tuesday, sorry,
you will see me again.

01:16:51.700 --> 01:16:54.880 align:middle line:84%
I will start with
step 4 from the top.

01:16:54.880 --> 01:16:58.750 align:middle line:84%
But maybe as an exercise,
you have five days.

01:16:58.750 --> 01:17:01.210 align:middle line:84%
You can try to imagine
how this will continue.

01:17:01.210 --> 01:17:03.570 align:middle line:84%
So at least try to
well, just write

01:17:03.570 --> 01:17:06.060 align:middle line:84%
down what is the outcome
of Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers,

01:17:06.060 --> 01:17:10.050 align:middle line:84%
and try to think how we can
use that to eventually get what

01:17:10.050 --> 01:17:12.250 align:middle line:90%
we want, at least this claim.

01:17:12.250 --> 01:17:14.760 align:middle line:84%
Then I will explain how
this claim, together

01:17:14.760 --> 01:17:16.560 align:middle line:84%
with uniformization
lemma, allows

01:17:16.560 --> 01:17:19.010 align:middle line:90%
us to conclude what we want.

01:17:19.010 --> 01:17:26.000 align:middle line:90%